text: A dry dam is a type of dam that is designed to control flooding. It normally holds back no water and allows the channel to flow freely, except during periods of intense flow that would otherwise cause flooding downstream.
A diversionary dam is a type of dam that is designed to divert all or a portion of the flow of a river from its natural course.
A weapons test site is categorized as a type of anthropogenic geographic feature characterized by being a region where weapons, typically those of a military nature, are tested.
A nuclear weapons test site is a type of weapons test site defined as a site at which nuclear weapons are, or have been, tested.

A military training area is an anthropogenic geographic feature and a type of environment utilized, at least in part, for defense purposes. It is defined as a region in which military personnel train.

A park is classified as an anthropogenic geographic feature and falls under a category that engages in activities which are a combination of conservation-focused active ecosystem management processes and the utilization of an environment for recreation. Furthermore, a park is defined as a bounded area of land, or water, typically in its natural or semi-natural (landscaped) state, designated for a specific purpose, often related to recreation or conservation.
A pier is a type of transport feature that is typically adjacent to some water body. It is defined as a raised walkway over water, supported by piles or pillars.

An archeological site is a type of site that is defined as a place (or group of physical sites) in which evidence of past activity is preserved (either prehistoric or historic or contemporary). Furthermore, it is, has been, or may be investigated using the discipline of archaeology.

A sports facility is a type of human construction and also falls under the category of entities that participate in the usage of an environment for recreation. It is defined as a building or region where sports activities can be carried out.
A winter sports facility is a type of sports facility and is defined as a sports facility constructed for skiing and allied sports that require snow and/or ice.

A calanque is a type of valley that is specifically characterized by being adjacent to or part of an area that includes the ocean and sea. Furthermore, it is defined by its composition, being primarily made up of limestone. Additionally, a calanque is defined as a deep valley with steep sides, typically of limestone, that is in part submerged by the sea.
A city is defined as a type of dense settlement and an incorporated populated place, broadly synonymous with an urban area.

The freshwater biome is the same as an entity that lies at the intersection of the aquatic biome and an entity that is at least determined by an entity that is the intersection of a water body and an entity that is at least composed primarily of fresh water. This biome is a type of both aquatic biome and freshwater ecosystem. The freshwater biome is defined as an aquatic biome determined by a body of freshwater and is also related to the synonym freshwater realm.
The large river biome is a type of freshwater river biome, defined as a freshwater river biome that is determined by a large river.

The large river headwater biome is a type of freshwater river biome, which is characterized as part of the larger river biome and notably includes at least some headwaters. It is defined as a freshwater river biome determined by the headwaters of a large river.

The large river delta biome is defined as a freshwater river biome characterized by the delta of a large river. It is a subtype of both the freshwater river biome and a biome that includes at least a part of some large river or delta.
The small river biome is a type of freshwater river biome, defined as a freshwater river biome determined by a small river.
A large freshwater lake biome is a type of freshwater lake biome, defined as a freshwater biome characterized by a large lake.
A small freshwater lake biome is a type of freshwater lake biome defined as a freshwater lake biome characterized by a small lake.

The xeric basin biome is a type of freshwater biome and is also characterized as a type that encompasses at least some parts of freshwater springs. It is defined as a biome which has little permanent surface water and a low relative abundance of springs.

Rock is a type of solid environmental material and something that is at least somewhat hard. It is distinct from mineral material. A rock is defined as a naturally occurring solid aggregate of one or more minerals or mineraloids.

Mine drainage is a type of watercourse and is something that is at least part of some mine. It is defined as the outflow of water from a mine. Additionally, mine drainage is related to the synonyms acid and metalliferous drainage, as well as acid rock drainage.

Acid mine drainage is synonymous with acid rock drainage and is defined as mine drainage with an acidic pH. It is both a type of mine drainage and a type of substance that has at least some acidic quality. This term also refers to something that is the intersection of mine drainage and something that has at least some acidic quality.

Soil is a type of environmental material and is broadly synonymous with regolith. It is a part of the pedosphere and is primarily composed of minerals, including varying proportions of sand, silt, and clay, as well as organic material such as humus, interstitial gases, liquids, and a broad range of resident micro- and macroorganisms. Soil also contains mineral material and substances that are an intersection of chemical entities and nutrients. It has qualities such as being porous and dispositions like the water-holding capacity of soil.

A marine water body is a type of lentic water body and a type of hydroform. It is also characterized as something that is at least part of some marine biome. The definition of a marine water body is a significant accumulation of water which is part of a marine biome. Additionally, it has exact synonyms which are "body of marine water" and "marine waterbody."

A slope is a type of landform, which is characterized by being a part of the planetary surface that lies between the peak of an elevation or the bottom of a depression and the relatively flat surrounding land. This type of landform falls into the category of features that are at least partly elevated or depressed. Additionally, a slope is recognized for having a quality that is, in some way, sloped. In terms of terminology, "slope" is synonymously related to "flank" and "side."
Waste water is a type of contaminated water and a type of waste material. It is defined as water that has been adversely affected in quality by anthropogenic influence.

Fecal material is a type of excreta material, which is also defined as an excreta material composed primarily of feces. Feces, in turn, consist of waste products expelled from an animal's digestive tract through the anus (or cloaca) during defecation. This material is also known by exact synonyms such as faeces material and feces material. Additionally, it has related synonyms including droppings, frass, and pellet, indicating its various forms or references.

Air is a type of gaseous environmental material and is defined as the mixture of gases that surrounds the planet Earth, roughly comprising by molar content/volume: 78% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.038% carbon dioxide, trace amounts of other gases, and a variable amount (average around 1%) of water vapor. It is primarily composed of dinitrogen and at least has parts of dioxygen, carbon dioxide, argon molecular entity, and water vapor.

Liquid water is identified as a type of liquid environmental material and something that is at least composed primarily of water. It is defined as an environmental material primarily composed of dihydrogen oxide in its liquid form. Additionally, liquid water is broadly synonymous with water.

Sediment is a type of environmental material that possesses qualities such as being porous and granular. It is defined as an environmental substance comprised of any particulate matter that can be transported by fluid flow, eventually being deposited as a layer of solid particles on the bed or bottom of a body of water or other liquid.

Dust is a type of particulate and solid environmental material, which is characterized by having at least some quality of being dry. It is defined as particulate environmental material with diameters less than 500 micrometers.

Saline water is a type of liquid water that is defined as water which contains a significant concentration of dissolved salts. It is characterized by having at least some increased osmolarity and increased levels of sodium chloride. Additionally, saline water is exactly synonymous with salt water.

Fresh water is a type of liquid water and is defined as water which has a low concentration of dissolved solutes, particularly that of sodium chloride. Furthermore, fresh water is exactly synonymous with freshwater and is relatedly synonymous with sweet water.
Hypersaline water is a type of saline water, defined as water that contains a highly increased concentration of dissolved salts, surpassing the average salinity of seawater.

Igneous rock, which is a type of rock, is defined as rock formed from molten magma. It is the same as something that intersects with rock and something that at least derives from some lava. Furthermore, igneous rock is also identified as a type of entity that at least derives from some lava.

Plutonic rock is a type of igneous rock, which is defined as an igneous rock that results from the crystallization of magma below the surface of the Earth. Additionally, it is synonymously related to intrusive rock.

Volcanic rock is defined as an igneous rock that results from magma reaching the surface either as lava or fragmental ejecta, and it is the same as something that intersects with rock and something that, at the very least, is formed as a result of some volcanic eruption. Additionally, volcanic rock is a type of rock and also a type of something that is formed as a result of some volcanic eruption.

Sedimentary rock is a type of rock defined as a rock formed by the deposition of either clastic sediments, organic matter, or chemical precipitates (evaporites), followed by the compaction of the particulate matter and cementation during diagenesis.

Metamorphic rock is a type of rock defined as one formed by subjecting any rock type, including previously-formed metamorphic rock, to different temperature and pressure conditions than those in which the original rock was formed. These temperatures and pressures are always higher than those at the Earth's surface and must be sufficiently high to change the original minerals into other mineral types or into other forms of the same minerals, such as by recrystallisation.

Sewage is a type of wastewater that is the same as something that intersects waste water and something that is at least composed primarily of some animal waste material. Moreover, sewage is defined as wastewater that is contaminated with feces or urine.
Brackish water is a type of saline water, defined as water which has a higher salinity than fresh water but a lower salinity than marine water.

The aquatic biome, which is a type of both biome and aquatic ecosystem, is characterized as a biome determined by a water body and encompasses ecological climax communities adapted to life in or on water. It is identified as the same as the intersection of a biome and an entity that is at least determined by some water body. Furthermore, it is defined as a biome which is determined by a water body and which has ecological climax communities adapted to life in or on water.

A carcass is a type of organic object that is characterized by being at least somewhat dead and derives from some anatomical entity. It is defined as the dead body of an animal and is synonymously related to the term corpse.
A biofilm is a type of mass of biological material, defined as a complex aggregation of microorganisms marked by the excretion of a protective and adhesive matrix; it usually adheres to a substratum.
A meteorite is defined as a natural object originating in outer space that survives an impact with a planetary surface without being destroyed and is a type of mass of solid material.
Wood is a type of organic and solid environmental material.

Surface water is a type of liquid water and also falls under the category of water that is found on the surface of an astronomical object. Additionally, it represents the intersection of water surfaces and parts of astronomical objects. Moreover, surface water is defined as water that is found on the surface of an astronomical object.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:wastewater_treatment_plant rdfs:subClassOf :waste_treatment_plant .
text: wastewater treatment plant is a type of waste treatment plant.
Sludge is a type of anthropogenic environmental material, defined as the residual semi-solid material left from domestic or industrial processes, or wastewater treatment processes.

Anaerobic sediment is defined as sediment characterized by the absence of oxygen and is the same as the intersection of sediment and something that has at least some anaerobic quality. It is a type of sediment and also a type of something that has at least some anaerobic quality. Furthermore, anaerobic sediment has an exact synonym, which is anoxic sediment.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:activated_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :sludge .
text: activated sludge is a type of sludge.

Urine material is a type of excreta material and also a type of substance that is at least primarily composed of urine. It is defined as an excreta material which is primarily made up of urine, a liquid excreta that contains water and waste products produced by the kidneys, stored in the bladder, and expelled from the body through the urethra.
Chondrite is a type of stony meteorite defined as a stony meteorite that has not been modified due to melting or differentiation of the parent body.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:stony_meteorite rdfs:subClassOf :meteorite .
text: stony meteorite is a type of meteorite.
An achondrite is a type of stony meteorite that is defined as being made of material similar to terrestrial basalts or plutonic rocks.
A stony iron meteorite is a type of meteorite defined as a meteorite that consists of a mixture of iron-nickel metal and silicate minerals.
An iron meteorite is a type of meteorite that is overwhelmingly composed of nickel-iron alloys.

Limestone is a type of sedimentary rock which is defined as a sedimentary rock that is primarily composed of calcium carbonate in the forms of calcite or aragonite. It is a result of chemical precipitation processes that occur in water bodies, leading to the formation of calcium carbonate. This indicates that limestone derives from an intersection of processes that involve chemical precipitation and the presence of calcium carbonate.
Chalk is a type of limestone that is soft, white, and porous. It is defined as a variety of limestone which possesses qualities of being white and porous.
Sandstone is a type of clastic sedimentary rock, defined as a sedimentary rock composed mainly of sand-size mineral or rock grains.

Shale is a type of clastic sedimentary rock, defined as a fine-grained sedimentary rock whose original constituents were clays or muds. It is characterized by thin laminae breaking with an irregular curving fracture, often splintery and usually parallel to the often-indistinguishable bedding plane.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:raw_primary_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :sludge .
text: raw primary sludge is a type of sludge.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:secondary_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :sludge .
text: secondary sludge is a type of sludge.
Biosolids, a type of sludge, are defined as a treated form of sludge, sometimes used as a fertilizer in agriculture.
Oil sludge is a type of contaminated sludge with a definition: A solid or gel in motor oil caused by the oil gelling or solidifying, usually at temperatures lower than 100 degrees Celsius.

Oil spill is a type of anthropogenic contamination feature and is defined as the result of the unintentional release of liquid petroleum hydrocarbon into the environment as a result of human activity.

An oil seep, which is a type of liquid astronomical body part and something that is composed primarily of oil, is defined as the result of the release of natural hydrocarbons to the surface of the earth, including beneath the sea, by natural geological processes.
Gold mine drainage is a type of mine drainage, defined as the drainage formed as a result of the mining of gold.

Deep marine sediment, which is a type of marine sediment, is defined as sediment that accumulates in the flat or very gently sloping areas of the deep ocean basin floor. It is also known by its exact synonym, deep marine sediments, and has a related synonym, pelagic sediment, which is considered an alternative name. The three main types of deep marine sediment, also referred to as pelagic sediment, include siliceous oozes, calcareous oozes, and red clays.

Chemically enriched sediment is a type of sediment that is identical to the intersection of sediment and any entity that has at least increased levels of some chemical entity. Furthermore, it is defined as sediment which has increased levels of one or more chemical compounds.

Petroleum enriched sediment is defined as organically enriched sediment which also has increased levels of petroleum. This means it is both a type of organically enriched sediment and falls under the category of substances that have increased levels of petroleum. Essentially, petroleum enriched sediment represents the intersection between organically enriched sediment and substances with elevated petroleum levels.

Contaminated soil is a type of enriched soil and also a type that has increased levels of a material entity which plays a role as either a poison or an environmental contaminant. Furthermore, contaminated soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of some contaminant.
Creosote contaminated soil is a type of contaminated soil that has elevated concentrations of creosote, defined as soil which has increased levels of some creosote.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:sea_sand rdfs:subClassOf :sand .
text: sea sand is a type of sand.

An alkaline hot spring is a type of alkaline spring and it is also a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some alkaline water. Furthermore, it is a type of entity that is at least adjacent to an entity that is an intersection of something that is water and something that at least has the quality of an increased temperature. An alkaline hot spring is defined as an alkaline spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows.

An acidic hot spring is a type of acidic spring and also a type of formation that is adjacent to acidic water. Additionally, it is characterized as being adjacent to an area where water intersects with regions of increased temperature, indicating the presence of geothermal energy. An acidic hot spring is defined as an acidic spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows. Furthermore, "acid hot spring" is considered a broad synonym for an acidic hot spring.

An alkaline salt lake is defined as a saline lake with a high pH and is synonymous with a soda lake. This type of lake is essentially an intersection of saline lakes and those that possess at least some alkaline quality. Therefore, an alkaline salt lake is both a type of saline lake and a type of entity that has some alkaline quality.

Arsenic-rich mud is defined as mud that has elevated concentrations of arsenic, which means it is the same as something that intersects with mud and something that has at least increased levels of some arsenic atom. Additionally, arsenic-rich mud is characterized as a type of mud and also as a type of substance that has at least increased levels of some arsenic atom.

A bioreactor is a specific type of biomaterial containment unit. It is defined as a biomaterial containment unit that is capable of containing a mass of environmental material which hosts an active collection of organisms and maintaining conditions that are conducive to one or more metabolic activities of the organisms it contains.

An anaerobic bioreactor is the same as something that is both a bioreactor and has at least some quality of being anaerobic. It is a type of bioreactor that, at a minimum, possesses the quality of being anaerobic. An anaerobic bioreactor is defined as a bioreactor in which the contained material is not oxygenated, meaning it is void of biologically consequential free oxygen.

An anaerobic dechlorinating bioreactor, which is a specific type of anaerobic bioreactor, is defined as a device or system that supports a biologically active environment. It is a vessel where a chemical process involving organisms or biochemically active substances derived from such organisms is carried out. This process can be either aerobic or anaerobic.

An aerobic bioreactor is a type of bioreactor that is essentially the intersection of a bioreactor and something that possesses at least some aerobic quality. It is defined as a bioreactor in which the contained material is well-oxygenated.

Stream sediment, which is a type of sediment, is equivalent to something that intersects with sediment and something that is at least adjacent to a stream. Additionally, stream sediment is categorized as a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some stream.

A mesophilic sulfur spring is a type of sulfur spring defined as a sulfur spring through which water flows at a temperature optimal for the growth of mesophilic microorganisms, approximately 20 to 45 degrees Celsius.

Anaerobic sludge is the same as something that intersects with sludge and something that at least has the quality of being somewhat anaerobic. It is a type of sludge and also a type of something that at least has some anaerobic quality.

Hypolimnion is a type of lake layer and at least part of some meromictic lake, as well as being adjacent to some metalimnion. It is defined as the dense, bottom layer of water in a thermally-stratified lake, lying below the thermocline.

Epilimnion is a type of lake layer and is characterized as being at least part of or adjacent to the metalimnion in some meromictic lakes. It is defined as the top-most layer in a thermally stratified lake, occurring above the deeper hypolimnion. This layer is warmer and typically has a higher pH and dissolved oxygen concentration than the hypolimnion.
Metalimnion is a type of thermocline and is part of at least some lakes, characterized by being a cline where the temperature changes rapidly with depth within the lake.

Anaerobic mud, which is a type of mud and also a type of entity that possesses some quality of being anaerobic, is identical to something that intersects with mud and something that has at least the quality of being somewhat anaerobic. It is defined as mud which has no or negligible concentrations of dissolved oxygen. Furthermore, anaerobic mud has an exact synonym: anoxic mud.

Anaerobic stream sediment is the same as something that is an intersection of stream sediment and something that at least has the quality of being somewhat anaerobic. Furthermore, anaerobic stream sediment is a type of both anaerobic sediment and stream sediment.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:treated_wood rdfs:subClassOf :wood .
text: treated wood is a type of wood.

Arsenate treated wood is the same as something that is both wood and has at least increased levels of some arsenate 3. Additionally, arsenate treated wood is a type of treated wood and also a type of material that has at least increased levels of some arsenate 3.
A brackish estuary is a type of estuary defined as an estuary which is composed primarily of brackish water.

Beach sand is the same as something that intersects with something that is sand and something that is at least part of some sandy beach. Furthermore, beach sand is a type of sand and also a type of something that is at least part of some sandy beach.

A pebble is defined as a piece of rock that is derived from clastic rock and has a grain size of 4 to 64 millimeters. It is a type of piece of rock, and also a type of entity that at least derives from part of some clastic sedimentary rock.
Cobble is a type of piece of rock, defined as a piece of rock which has a grain size between 64 and 256 mm.
Leachate is a type of liquid water, defined as the liquid produced when water percolates through any permeable material. It can contain either dissolved or suspended material, or usually both.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:borax_leachate rdfs:subClassOf :leachate .
text: borax leachate is a type of leachate.

A calcite hot spring, also known precisely as a calcic hot spring, is categorized as a type of calcic spring. It is defined as a calcic spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows. This type of spring is characterized by being at least adjacent to an entity that intersects with water possessing a quality of increased temperature.

A cave wall is a type of solid surface layer, surface of an astronomical body, something that forms at least part of a cave, and something that possesses at least some vertical quality. Moreover, a cave wall is defined as a solid surface layer which forms part of the boundary between the cavity of a cave and its solid container and is roughly perpendicular to the cave floor.

Chromate contaminated soil is a type of metal contaminated soil and something that at least has increased levels of some chromate 2. It is defined as soil which has elevated concentrations of chromate.
Xylene contaminated soil is a type of contaminated soil and something that has increased levels of xylene. It is defined as soil which has elevated concentrations of xylene.
Coal mine lake sediment is a type of lake sediment that covers the bottom of a coal mine lake.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:coarse_beach_sand rdfs:subClassOf :beach_sand .
text: coarse beach sand is a type of beach sand.

Sea water is the same as something that intersects something that is saline water and something that is at least part of something that is a union of the ocean and the sea. It is a type of saline water and also a type of something that is at least part of something that is either an ocean or a sea. Sea water is defined as water which has physicochemical properties determined by the processes occurring in a sea or ocean. Additionally, sea water has the exact synonyms ocean water and seawater.

Coastal sea water is defined as sea water that is adjacent to a coast, which means it is the same as the intersection of sea water and anything that is at least adjacent to some sea coast. This type of sea water not only falls under the category of sea water but also qualifies as a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some sea coast. In terms of terminology, coastal sea water is broadly synonymous with coastal water and has exact synonyms including coastal ocean water, coastal oceanic water, and coastal seawater.
A biofilter is a type of bioreactor with the definition of being a bioreactor that captures and degrades pollutants through the biological processes maintained in the medium it contains.
A compost biofilter, which is a type of biofilter, is defined as a biofilter that contains compost and utilizes the microbial communities within it to degrade pollutants.

Radioactive sediment is the same as something that intersects sediment and something that has at least some quality of being radioactive. It is a type of chemically enriched sediment and also a type of something that has at least some quality of being radioactive.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:high_level_radioactive_sediment rdfs:subClassOf :radioactive_sediment .
text: high level radioactive sediment is a type of radioactive sediment.

A Superfund site is a type of area designated for waste storage, defined as a highly contaminated site designated by the United States of America's Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:stromatolite_mat rdfs:subClassOf :microbial_mat .
text: stromatolite mat is a type of microbial mat.
Ditch water is a type of fresh water that is at least partly found in some ditches.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:drilling_bore_water rdfs:subClassOf :liquid_water .
text: drilling bore water is a type of liquid water.

Estuarine mud is defined as mud which is part of an estuary. It is a type of mud that is the same as the intersection of mud and something that is at least part of some estuary. This implies that estuarine mud is also a type of something that is at least part of some estuary.

Fossil material is a type of solid environmental material and is something that results from the fossilization of organic material. It is defined as a solid environmental material formed by the replacement of organic substances, including those in soils and sediments, with mineral material.

A platinum mine is the same as an entity that intersects the characteristics of being a mine and also being capable of engaging in a material extraction process which notably has the output of some platinum ore. Additionally, a platinum mine falls under the category of mines. Furthermore, it is classified as a type of entity that is at least capable of undertaking some form of material extraction process that results in the output of platinum ore.

A gold mine is equivalent to an entity that intersects with both a mine and an entity capable of a material extraction process that, at the very least, outputs gold ore. Additionally, a gold mine is categorized as a type of mine and as a type of entity capable of a material extraction process with the capability to output gold ore.

A coal mine is the same as something that is both a mine and at least capable of a process that is an intersection of a material extraction process and has an output of some coal. Moreover, a coal mine is a type of mine. Additionally, a coal mine is a type of entity that is at least capable of a process which is an intersection of a material extraction process and has an output of some coal.
Compost is a type of manure, defined as manure that has been derived from the aerobically decomposed remnants of organic materials.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:hay_compost rdfs:subClassOf :compost .
text: hay compost is a type of compost.
A hospital is a type of healthcare facility characterized by being a building in which health care services are provided by specialized staff and equipment.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:contaminated_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :sludge .
text: contaminated sludge is a type of sludge.

1,4-Dioxane contaminated sludge is the same as something that is an intersection of sludge and something that at least has increased levels of 1,4-Dioxane. It is a type of contaminated sludge and also a type of something that at least has increased levels of 1,4-Dioxane.

The iron reducing zone of petroleum contaminated sediment is a type of environmental zone and is also identified as a part of some petroleum-enriched sediment. It is defined as a zone within a portion of petroleum contaminated sediment where iron-reducing processes occur.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:intertidal_sediment rdfs:subClassOf :sediment .
text: intertidal sediment is a type of sediment.

Naphthalene-enriched sediment is defined as organically enriched sediment that also has increased levels of naphthalene. It is a type of organically enriched sediment and is characterized by at least having increased levels of naphthalene.

A neutral hot spring is a type of neutral spring and also a type of entity that is adjacent to another entity, which intersects with water that has an increased temperature quality. Moreover, a neutral hot spring is defined as a neutral spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows.

Nitrobenzene enriched sediment is defined as organically enriched sediment that has increased levels of nitrobenzene. This type of sediment is both a kind of organically enriched sediment and a category that includes sediments with elevated levels of nitrobenzene. Essentially, nitrobenzene enriched sediment is identified as the intersection of organically enriched sediment and sediment that has increased levels of nitrobenzene.

An oil tank is a type of manufactured product defined as a manufactured container within which oil or other petrochemical products are stored and which these products are usually transported to end users or further storage facilities.
A subsurface landform is a type of landform that has an exact synonym, sub-surface landform, and is also related to or known as an underground physiographic feature.

An oil reservoir is a type of subsurface landform, which is also broadly synonymous with oil and gas reservoir as well as petroleum reservoir. It is a kind of entity that, at a minimum, contains some amount of petroleum and is primarily composed of substances that are both rock and either porous or broken. The definition of an oil reservoir is a subsurface landform that contains fluid hydrocarbons within porous or fractured rock formations.

Contaminated water, also known exactly as polluted water, is identical to liquid water that intersects with substances that have increased levels of chemical entities, which also have roles as environmental contaminants. This type of water is characterized by having elevated concentrations of chemicals that are considered environmental pollutants. Therefore, contaminated water is a specific kind of liquid water and is also defined by its significantly higher levels of chemicals that serve as environmental contaminants.
Animal litter is a type of environmental material defined as straw or other material strewn in an animal's enclosure (e.g., a stable) for it to sleep on and to absorb its faeces and urine.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:poultry_litter rdfs:subClassOf :animal_litter .
text: poultry litter is a type of animal litter.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:pulp_bleaching_waste_water rdfs:subClassOf :waste_water .
text: pulp bleaching waste water is a type of waste water.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:oil_field_production_water rdfs:subClassOf :liquid_water .
text: oil field production water is a type of liquid water.
Pyritic acid mine drainage, an exact synonym for acid mine drainage, is a type of acid mine drainage characterized by elevated levels of pyritic acid.
An aquarium is a type of vivarium, defined as a vivarium that simulates the submerged portions of an aquatic environment.

A saline water aquarium, which is a type of aquarium, is defined as an aquarium that contains saline water as its primary ecological medium. It is also related to and synonymously known as a saltwater aquarium.
A fresh water aquarium is a type of aquarium, defined as an aquarium that contains fresh water as its primary ecological medium.

A sandy beach is the same as an intersection of a beach and an entity that is at least composed primarily of sand. It is a type of beach and also a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of sand. Furthermore, a sandy beach is defined as a beach which is primarily composed of sand.
Sea ice is a type of water body derived ice, specifically something that at least derives from some sea water. It is defined as water ice which has formed by the freezing of sea water.
Cis dichloroethane contaminated sediment is a type of organically enriched sediment that is defined as organically enriched sediment with increased levels of cis-dichloroethane.

Organically enriched sediment is defined as chemically-enriched sediment that has increased levels of organic compounds. It is equivalent to the intersection of chemically enriched sediment and substances that have elevated levels of some organic molecular entity. Furthermore, organically enriched sediment is classified as a type of chemically enriched sediment, as well as a type of substance that possesses increased levels of some organic molecular entity.

Inorganically enriched sediment is defined as chemically enriched sediment that intersects with substances having increased levels of some inorganic molecular entities. It is a specific type of chemically enriched sediment and also falls under the category of substances that possess elevated levels of inorganic molecular entities. This sediment is characterized by its increased levels of inorganic compounds, providing a comprehensive definition that encompasses its chemical enrichment and inorganic molecular composition.

Anthropogenic contamination feature is a type of anthropogenic geographic feature, defined as an anthropogenic geographic feature which has increased levels of contaminants in its constituent materials.
An unexploded ordnance dump is a type of landfill and is defined as a dump that contains ammunition or other material intended for use during combat, which still has the potential to explode.
Coal mine waste material is a type of industrial waste material and is part of some coal mine. It is broadly synonymous with coal mine waste and is also relatedly referred to as coal refuse.
Self-heating coal mine waste material, which is a type of coal mine waste material, is broadly synonymous with self-heating coal mine waste.

Saline lake sediment is a type of lake sediment that is defined as sediment covering the bottom of a saline lake. It is also something that is at least adjacent to some saline lake and has a related synonym, soda lake sediment.
An aerobic sulfide oxidizing bioreactor, which is a type of aerobic bioreactor, is defined as an aerobic bioreactive system containing microbial communities capable of sulfide oxidation.

A thermophilic anaerobic methanogenic reactor is a type of anaerobic bioreactor that falls under the category of systems which at least contain processes some methanogenesis. It is defined as an anaerobic bioreactor which utilizes elevated temperatures and appropriate chemical substrates to facilitate the production of methane by microbial communities.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:thermophilic_granular_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :sludge .
text: thermophilic granular sludge is a type of sludge.

An anaerobic sludge blanket reactor is a type of anaerobic bioreactor defined as an anaerobic bioreactor capable of treating wastewater. This treatment occurs through the action of methanogenic microbes, which form a blanket of sludge due to the upward flow in the reactor.

A power plant is synonymous with a generating plant, generating station, power station, and powerhouse. It is defined as a building which contains one or more generators that convert mechanical energy into electrical energy through the relative motion between a magnetic field and a conductor, with the source of energy harnessed to turn the generator varying widely. This facility is the same as an entity that represents the intersection of being an industrial building and having the capability of generating energy, specifically through anthropogenic means while realizing some form of kinetic energy. Furthermore, a power plant is categorized as a type of industrial building and a type of entity that is at least capable of generating some form of energy, as well as being capable of anthropogenic energy generation and realizing kinetic energy.

A geothermal power plant is a specific type of power plant that intersects with facilities capable of anthropogenic energy generation and those that utilize geothermal energy. It is defined as a plant that leverages heat produced by the decay of radioactive isotopes within the Earth's mantle and crust, as well as residual primordial heat from the Earth's formation, to operate its generators. Essentially, a geothermal power plant is characterized by its ability to harness geothermal energy for the generation of power, positioning it within the realm of man-made energy production facilities.

A shop is a type of commercial building and is defined as a building in which a business presents a selection of goods and offers to trade or sell them to customers for money or other goods. It is also exactly synonymous with retail shop, retail store, and retailer.
A food shop is a type of shop characterized by offering food products for sale or trade.

Oligotrophic water is a type of liquid water characterized by a very low concentration of nutrients. It is defined as water that intersects with a decreased concentration of chemical entities that play a role as nutrients.

Eutrophic water is a type of liquid water and is defined as water with a high nutrient level. It is a type of substance that has increased levels of entities that intersect with chemical entities and have a role as nutrients.
Mesotrophic water is a type of liquid water defined as water with a nutrient level that is intermediate between eutrophic and oligotrophic.

A borehole is a type of human construction and a type of channel. It is also a type that at least partially overlaps with something that encompasses submerged beds, planetary landmasses, and bedrock. Additionally, a borehole is defined as a channel constructed by removing materials from land or submerged beds.
Pond water is a type of fresh water and is also something that constitutes at least part of some pond.

Arenosol is a type of soil defined as sandy soils, encompassing both soils developed in residual sands after in situ weathering of usually quartz-rich sediments or rock and soils developed in recently deposited sands such as dunes in deserts and beach lands. Moreover, Arenosol is exactly synonymous with psamment and sandy soil.

Anthrosol is a type of soil, which is also classified as a type of anthropogenic environmental material and something that results from some form of anthropisation. It is defined as soils that have been profoundly modified through human activities, including the addition of organic materials or household wastes, irrigation, and cultivation.

Alisol is a type of soil defined by its unique characteristics. These soils have a higher clay content in the subsoil than in the topsoil, a feature attributed to pedogenetic processes, particularly clay migration, leading to an argic subsoil horizon. Furthermore, Alisols are characterized by a low base saturation at certain depths and contain high-activity clays within the argic horizon. Unlike Albeluvisols, they do not exhibit albeluvic tonguing. Alisols are predominantly found in humid tropical, humid subtropical, and warm temperate regions.

Andosol is a type of soil, which is a kind of material that primarily derives from an intersection of environmental material and substances mainly composed of silica-based glass. Moreover, Andosols are defined as soils that develop in volcanic ejecta or glasses under almost any climate, excluding hyperarid climate conditions. However, Andosols can also develop in other silicate-rich materials under acidic weathering in humid and perhumid climates.

Albeluvisol is a type of soil, defined as Albeluvisols are soils that have, beginning within 1 meter of the soil surface, a clay illuviation horizon with an irregular or broken upper boundary, resulting in tonguing of bleached soil material into the illuviation horizon.

Acrisol is a type of ultisol and is defined as soils that exhibit a higher clay content in the subsoil compared to the topsoil. This characteristic is a result of pedogenetic processes, particularly clay migration, leading to the formation of an argic subsoil horizon. Furthermore, acrisols are identified by having low base saturation and low-activity clays at certain depths.

Cambisol is a type of soil defined by combining soils with at least an incipient subsurface soil formation. The transformation of parent material in Cambisols is evident from structure formation and mostly brownish discoloration, increasing clay percentage, and/or carbonate removal.

Cryosol is a type of frozen soil and also a type of something that constitutes at least part of some permafrost. Cryosols are defined as mineral soils formed in a permafrost environment where, if water is present, it primarily occurs in the form of ice, and cryogenic processes are the dominant soil-forming processes. Additionally, cryosol has a related synonym: gelisol.
Chernozem is a type of soil defined as soils with a thick black surface layer that is rich in organic matter. It is also related to the synonyms "black earth" and "boroll."

Durisol is a type of soil which is mainly associated with old surfaces in arid and semi-arid environments. It accommodates very shallow to moderately deep, moderately well- to well-drained soils that contain cemented secondary silica (SiO2) within 100 cm of the soil surface.

Calcisol is a type of soil defined as Calcisols, soils in which there is substantial secondary accumulation of lime. These soils are common in highly calcareous parent materials and are widespread in arid and semi-arid environments. Additionally, Calcisol has an exact synonym, Calcarosol.

Kastanozem is a type of soil defined as Kastanozems, which are dry grassland soils. These include the zonal soils of the short-grass steppe belt located south of the Eurasian tall-grass steppe belt with Chernozems. Kastanozems share a similar profile to that of Chernozems, however, the humus-rich surface horizon of Kastanozems is thinner and not as dark as that of the Chernozems. Additionally, Kastanozems exhibit a more prominent accumulation of secondary carbonates.

Leptosol is a type of soil defined as very shallow soils over continuous rock and soils that are extremely gravelly and/or stony. They are azonal soils and particularly common in mountainous regions. Additionally, leptosol has narrow synonyms, including gravelly soil and stony soil.

Lixisol is a type of soil defined by having a higher clay content in the subsoil than in the topsoil, a characteristic attributed to pedogenetic processes, notably clay migration, which results in an argic subsoil horizon. Additionally, Lixisols are distinguished by their high base saturation and the presence of low-activity clays at specific depths.

Histosol is identified as a type of soil. It is defined by the characteristic that Histosols comprise soils formed in organic material, which can range from soils developed predominantly in moss peat within boreal, arctic, and subarctic regions, to moss peat, reeds/sedge peat (fen), and forest peat in temperate regions, extending to mangrove peat and swamp forest peat in the humid tropics. Furthermore, while Histosols can be found at all altitudes, the vast majority is located in lowlands.

Gleysol is a type of soil defined as Gleysols are wetland soils that, unless drained, are saturated with groundwater for long enough periods to develop a characteristic gleyic colour pattern. This pattern essentially comprises reddish, brownish, or yellowish colors at ped surfaces and/or in the upper soil layer or layers, in combination with greyish/bluish colors inside the peds and/or deeper in the soil. Additionally, gleysol is also related to the synonym "gley soil."

Gypsisol is a type of soil defined as Gypsisols, which are soils with substantial secondary accumulation of gypsum (calcium sulfate). These soils are found in the driest parts of the arid climate zone.

Ferralsol is a type of soil defined as the classical, deeply weathered, red or yellow soils of the humid tropics. These soils are characterized by diffuse horizon boundaries, a clay assemblage dominated by low-activity clays (mainly kaolinite), and a high content of sesquioxides. Ferralsol is also related to oxisol as a synonym.

Nitisol is a type of soil defined as Nitisols, which are deep, well-drained, red, tropical soils with diffuse horizon boundaries. These soils have a subsurface horizon that contains more than 30 percent clay and exhibits moderate to strong angular blocky structure elements. These elements easily fall apart into characteristic shiny, polyhedric (nutty) elements. While weathering in Nitisols is relatively advanced, these soils are far more productive than most other red, tropical soils.

Luvisol is a type of soil. It is defined as soils that have a higher clay content in the subsoil than in the topsoil, a characteristic attributed to pedogenetic processes, particularly clay migration, which results in an argic subsoil horizon. Additionally, Luvisols are characterized by high-activity clays throughout the argic horizon and exhibit high base saturation at certain depths.

Phaeozem is a type of soil characterized by its accommodation in soils of relatively wet grassland and forest regions located in moderately continental climates. This soil type is closely related to Chernozems and Kastanozems but undergoes more intensive leaching. As a result, Phaeozems possess dark, humus-rich surface horizons that, when compared with Chernozems and Kastanozems, contain lower concentrations of bases. Furthermore, Phaeozems might exhibit the presence or absence of secondary carbonates, yet they maintain a high base saturation within the upper metre of the soil.

Plinthosol is identified as a type of soil characterized by the presence of plinthite, petroplinthite, or pisoliths. The definition of Plinthosols encompasses soils containing plinthite, which is an iron-rich (and in certain cases, also manganese-rich) mixture. This mixture is poor in humus and comprises kaolinitic clay, along with other products of intense weathering like gibbsite, quartz, and various constituents. Upon exposure to repeated wetting and drying processes, plinthite undergoes an irreversible transformation into a layer characterized by hard nodules, a hardpan, or irregular aggregates. Petroplinthite is described as a continuous, fractured, or broken sheet that consists of connected, strongly cemented to indurated nodules or mottles. Additionally, pisoliths are identified as discrete, strongly cemented to indurated nodules. Both petroplinthite and pisoliths are the result of the hardening of plinthite.

Planosol is a type of soil defined as soils with a light-colored, surface horizon that exhibits signs of periodic water stagnation and abruptly overlies a dense, slowly permeable subsoil, which contains significantly more clay than the surface horizon.

Solonchak is a type of soil defined by its high concentration of soluble salts at some point during the year. These soils are primarily found in arid and semi-arid climate zones, as well as coastal regions across various climates.

Umbrisol is a type of soil defined as soils in which organic matter has accumulated within the mineral surface soil, in most cases with low base saturation, to the extent that it significantly affects the behavior and utilization of the soil.

Vertisol is a type of soil defined by its high content of expansive clay known as montmorillonite, which forms deep cracks in drier seasons or years. This alternate shrinking and swelling leads to self-mulching, where the soil material mixes itself consistently. As a result, vertisols feature an extremely deep A horizon and lack a B horizon.

Solonetz is a type of soil characterized by a dense, strongly structured, clayey subsurface horizon with a high proportion of adsorbed sodium (Na) and/or magnesium (Mg) ions. Additionally, Solonetz soils that contain free soda (Na2CO3) exhibit strong alkalinity, with a field pH greater than 8.5.

Regosol is a type of soil defined as forming a taxonomic remnant group that includes all soils not fitting into any other Reference Soil Groups (RSGs). Specifically, Regosols are characterized by being very weakly developed mineral soils in unconsolidated materials. They lack a mollic or umbric horizon, are not very shallow, nor are they very rich in gravels (unlike Leptosols), sandy (unlike Arenosols), or composed of fluvic materials (unlike Fluvisols). Notably, Regosols are found extensively in eroding lands, particularly in regions that are arid, semi-arid, or mountainous.

Podzol is a type of soil defined as soils with a typically ash-grey upper subsurface horizon, which is bleached by the loss of organic matter and iron oxides, situated above a dark accumulation horizon with brown, reddish, or black illuviated humus and/or reddish Fe compounds. These soils occur in humid areas in the boreal and temperate zones and, locally, also in the tropics. Podzol is exactly synonymous with podsol and is relatedly referred to as podosolic soil.

Loam is a type of soil and also falls under the category of something that possesses at least some soil texture characteristics. It is defined as a soil composed of approximately equal proportions of sand and silt, with a smaller proportion of clay.
Agricultural soil is a type of soil that is part of at least some agricultural ecosystems. It is defined as soil which is part of an ecosystem used for agricultural activities.
Dune soil is a type of upland soil and is defined as soil which is part of some dune, indicating that it is a type of something that at least part of some dune.

Forest soil shares the same characteristics as something that intersects soil and something that is, at a minimum, located in a forested area. It is a type of soil and also a type of entity that is at least located in some forested area. Furthermore, forest soil is defined as a portion of soil which is found in a forested area.
Clay soil is a type of soil that is at least composed primarily of clay, and it is defined as soil which is primarily composed of clay.

Garden soil is identical to an intersection of soil with something that is, at a minimum, located in a garden. It is a specific type of soil that is part of, or located in, a garden. Furthermore, garden soil is defined as a portion of soil found in a garden.

Waste material is defined as a material that is not the desired output of a process and is typically the input of a process which removes it from its producer, such as a disposal process. It is the same as something that intersects environmental material and something that has at least one waste role. Furthermore, waste material is a type of environmental material and also a type of something that has at least one waste role.
Chicken breeding waste material, which is a type of agricultural waste, is also broadly referred to as chicken breeding waste and is relatedly known as chicken yard waste.

Industrial waste material, which is a type of waste material, is defined as liquid, solid, and gaseous wastes originating from the manufacture of specific products. It is also broadly synonymous with industrial waste.
A sphagnum bog is a type of peatland, which is defined as a peatland dominated by species of the Bryophyte Sphagnum.
A thermocline is a type of fluid cline and is defined as a cline across which temperature changes rapidly.
A chemocline is a type of fluid cline, defined as a cline across which the chemical composition of a fluid changes rapidly.

A nuclear power plant is defined as a power plant that uses heat generated by radioactive decay in a nuclear reactor to convert water into steam, which then drives turbines in electrical generators through pressure. It is equivalent to an entity that is both a power plant and capable of anthropogenic generation of energy while also realizing nuclear energy. Additionally, a nuclear power plant is categorized as a type of power plant that includes at least one nuclear power reactor and is capable of generating energy through anthropogenic means, specifically by realizing nuclear energy.
A waste treatment plant, which has the exact synonym WWTP, is a type of industrial building.
Fluvisol is a type of soil that is defined as genetically young, azonal soils found in alluvial deposits.

Stagnosol is a type of soil defined as soils with a perched water table that exhibit redoximorphic features caused by surface water. These soils are characterized by being periodically wet and mottled in both the topsoil and subsoil, which may or may not contain concretions and/or bleaching.

Technosol is a type of soil that is at least partially part of the technosphere. It is defined as soils whose properties and pedogenesis are dominated by their technical origin, including a significant amount of artifacts, or those that are sealed by technic hard rock. These soils contain artifacts, which are items recognizably made or extracted from the earth by humans, or are sealed by technic hard rock, a material created by humans with properties unlike natural rock. Technosols encompass soils from various human activities and constructions, including wastes like landfills, sludge, cinders, mine spoils, and ashes, pavements with their underlying unconsolidated materials, soils with geomembranes, and constructed soils in human-made materials.
Animal waste material, which is a type of organic waste material, is broadly synonymous with animal waste.

A back arc basin is recognized as a type of structural basin that also falls under a broader category, simply known as a basin, with an exact synonym being "backarc basin." It is defined as a depression in the sea floor resulting from the collision of continental plates. The process involves the sinking plate's weight causing the overlying plate to stretch and thin, ultimately forming a basin in the overlying plate. This stretching of the Earth's crust in these basins can extend to the point of cracking, allowing magma to emerge from the mantle beneath. Consequently, back arc basins often host active volcanoes and hydrothermal vents. Moreover, a back arc basin is described as a type of entity that is partially integrated with entities like the ocean floor and the sea floor.
An ocean basin is a type of structural basin and is defined as a structural basin that is below sea level. Additionally, it is a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some ocean.

Hay is recognized as a type of agricultural environmental material. It is defined as grass, legumes, or other herbaceous plants that have been cut, dried, and stored for use as animal fodder, particularly for grazing livestock such as cattle, horses, goats, and sheep.

Adobe is a type of manufactured product, anthropogenic environmental material, and solid environmental material. It is also defined as a natural building material made from sand, clay, water, and some kind of fibrous or organic material (such as sticks, straw, and/or manure). Furthermore, Adobe is characterized by containing at least some parts of clay and sand.

Alluvial soil is a type of soil that is formed as a result of erosion and water flow processes. This soil, defined as soil which has been eroded and influenced by flowing water and redeposited in a non-marine setting, is an output of erosion.
Bagasse is a type of waste material and is defined as the biomass remaining after sugarcane stalks are crushed to extract their juice. It is also exactly synonymous with sugarcane bagasse.
Organic waste material, which is a type of biological waste material, is broadly synonymous with organic waste.

An air conditioning unit is a type of manufactured product that is capable of removing heat and controlling the humidity of the air within a site. It has broad synonyms including A/C, A/C unit, and air conditioner.
Oil-contaminated soil is a type of contaminated soil and is characterized as something that has increased levels of some oil. It is defined as soil which has elevated concentrations of oil.
A warm seep is a type of seep that is part of at least some portion of an ocean.

Clay is categorized as a type of particulate environmental material and is defined as a particulate environmental material which is composed primarily of clay particles, with only minor proportions of other materials, demonstrates plasticity when wet, and is capable of hardening when dried or fired. It is further characterized as a substance that must have, at the very least, a part that includes some particle of clay, a characteristic that is granular, and a quality that is porous. Moreover, clay is entirely distinct and separate from silt.

Fuel oil is a type of oil that is a type of something which at least has the role of some fossil fuel. It is also a type of something that is at least composed primarily of substances that are a union of alkanes, aromatic compounds, and cyclic hydrocarbons. Fuel oil is defined as an oil which is liquid at room temperature (approximately 20 degrees Celsius), intended to be burned in a furnace or boiler for the generation of heat or used in an engine for the generation of power, obtained from petroleum distillation, either as a distillate or a residue, and composed of long hydrocarbon chains, particularly alkanes, cycloalkanes, and aromatics. Furthermore, fuel oil has exact synonyms such as furnace oil, heavy oil, and marine fuel.

Petroleum is a type of oil and also a type of fossil fuel. It is defined as a naturally occurring flammable liquid consisting of a complex mixture of hydrocarbons of various molecular weights and other liquid organic compounds that are found in geologic formations beneath planetary surfaces. Additionally, petroleum is related to the synonym "crude oil."

Oil is a type of liquid and hydrocarbon-based environmental material that at least has some hydrophobic quality. It is defined as a nonpolar, hydrophobic, and lipophilic material which is a viscous liquid at ambient temperatures (about 20 degrees Celsius) or slightly warmer.
Silage is a type of agricultural environmental material defined as a fermented, high-moisture forage that can be fed to ruminants.
Animal manure, which is manure derived from the waste products of animals, is a type of manure.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:fresh_animal_manure rdfs:subClassOf :animal_manure .
text: fresh animal manure is a type of animal manure.

Mushroom compost is a type of compost that is defined as a compost which generally consists of a combination of wheat straw, dried blood, horse manure, and ground chalk, composted together. It is the residual compost waste generated by industrial mushroom production.
An animal house is a type of house with the definition of being a house used for sheltering non-human animals.

A cow shed is a type of animal house, specifically used to shelter cows. It is defined as an animal house for cows and is exactly synonymous with byre, cattle shed, cow barn, cow house, cowhouse, and cowshed. Additionally, it has a narrow synonym, milking shed.
A piggery is a type of animal house, specifically an animal house used to house pigs.

A sewage plant is a type of waste treatment plant and is defined as a waste treatment plant equipped to treat sewage such that its potential for environmental contamination is reduced. It has the exact synonym "sewage treatment plant" and a related synonym "sewage treatment works."
Brine is a type of hypersaline water, which is defined as water saturated or nearly saturated with salt (NaCl).

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:bacon_curing_brine rdfs:subClassOf :brine .
text: bacon curing brine is a type of brine.
Drinking water is a type of fresh water and is defined as water which may be consumed by humans with no adverse effects on their health. It also has the exact synonym "potable water."

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:distilled_water rdfs:subClassOf :liquid_water .
text: distilled water is a type of liquid water.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:grass_silage rdfs:subClassOf :silage .
text: grass silage is a type of silage.

A manufactured product is defined as a material entity that has been processed by humans or their technology in any way, including both intermediate and final products. It is the same as something that is both a material entity and at least the output of some manufacturing process. Moreover, a manufactured product is a type of material entity as well as a type of something that is at least the output of some manufacturing process. Additionally, "manufactured good" is an exact synonym for a manufactured product.

Glue is a type of function that is defined as a function realized by an environmental material when used to bind material entities together. It has broad synonym paste and exact synonyms adhesive and mucilage.

Metal contaminated soil is a type of contaminated soil that is characterized by having elevated concentrations of metals. This means it is something that at least has increased levels of some metal atom, defined as soil which has elevated concentrations of metals.

Enriched soil is defined as a type of soil that intersects with soil and at least has increased levels of some material entity, meaning it is a portion of soil with elevated levels of some material entity.

Sarcosine enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of sarcosine, making it a type of enriched soil that also falls into the category of substances with at least increased levels of sarcosine. Furthermore, sarcosine enriched soil is equivalent to an intersection between enriched soil and substances that have increased levels of sarcosine.

Trimethylamine enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil that has elevated levels of trimethylamine. It is identified as a type of enriched soil and also falls into the category of substances that have at least increased levels of trimethylamine. Essentially, trimethylamine enriched soil is equivalent to the intersection of enriched soil and substances with elevated levels of trimethylamine.

Skatole enriched soil is defined as a type of enriched soil that also falls into the category of substances with at least increased levels of skatole. This means it shares characteristics with both something that enriches soil and something that has elevated skatole levels, essentially marking the intersection of these two properties. Specifically, a portion of skatole enriched soil is identified as a portion of soil that possesses elevated levels of skatole.
Ethanol enriched soil is a type of enriched soil characterized by having increased levels of ethanol. It is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of ethanol.

Acetamide enriched soil is a specific kind of enriched soil that also falls under the category of substances with at least increased levels of some acetamide. It is equivalent to the intersection of enriched soil and substances that have increased levels of acetamide. Furthermore, acetamide enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of acetamide.

Pantothenate enriched soil is a specific type of enriched soil that also falls under the category of substances with at least increased levels of pantothenate. It is identical to the intersection of substances that enrich soil and those that have elevated levels of pantothenate. Furthermore, pantothenate enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil that contains elevated levels of pantothenate.

Testosterone enriched soil is identified as being the same as the intersection between enriched soil and substances that have at least increased levels of testosterone. It is categorized as a type of enriched soil as well as a type that has elevated levels of testosterone. Moreover, testosterone enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil that contains elevated levels of testosterone.

Kynurenate enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of kynurenate. It is a specific type of enriched soil and also falls under the category of substances that have increased levels of some kynurenate. Essentially, kynurenate enriched soil represents the intersection of enriched soil and substances that have at least increased levels of kynurenate.

Threonine enriched soil is identical to the intersection of enriched soil and something that has at least increased levels of threonine. It is a subtype of both enriched soil and something that has at least elevated levels of threonine. Threonine enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil that possesses elevated levels of threonine.

Salicylate enriched soil is defined as soil with elevated levels of salicylate, and it is a type of enriched soil that intersects with soils having at least increased levels of some salicylate. This means that salicylate enriched soil is both a category of enriched soil and a category of soil that has increased levels of salicylate.

Poly beta hydroxybutyrate enriched soil is equivalent to the intersection of enriched soil and substances that possess elevated levels of poly hydroxybutyrate. It is categorized both as a type of enriched soil and as a type that has increased levels of some poly hydroxybutyrate. Furthermore, poly beta hydroxybutyrate enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of poly-beta-hydroxybutyrate.
L tartrate enriched soil is a type of enriched soil defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of L-(+)-tartrate.

Quinate enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of quinate, which is both a type of enriched soil and a type of substance that has increased levels of some quinate. This means that quinate enriched soil shares the same characteristics as something that intersects the properties of being enriched soil and something that has at least increased levels of some quinate.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:tap_water rdfs:subClassOf :fresh_water .
text: tap water is a type of fresh water.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:bore_hole_water rdfs:subClassOf :liquid_water .
text: bore hole water is a type of liquid water.

A tannery, which is a type of industrial building, is defined as a building in which the skins of animals are treated with chemicals to alter the structure of their constituent proteins, thereby creating leather.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:horse_manure rdfs:subClassOf :animal_manure .
text: horse manure is a type of animal manure.
Pig manure, which is primarily composed of pig feces, is a type of animal manure.

An industrial building is defined as a building within which goods are produced and, optionally, stored, or within which services are rendered. It is the same as something that is both a building and at least participates in some usage of an environment for industry. Additionally, an industrial building is classified as a type of building and also as a type of entity that at least participates in some usage of an environment for industry.
A dairy is a type of industrial building with the definition that it is a building in which animal milk is harvested and, optionally, processed for human consumption.

A food processing building is a type of industrial building with a specific definition. It is described as a building in which materials that contain or consist of essential body nutrientssuch as carbohydrates, fats, proteins, vitamins, or mineralsand may be ingested and assimilated by an organism to produce energy, stimulate growth, and maintain life are transformed into alternative forms.

A bakery is a type of industrial building defined as a building in which raw flour-based food is baked in an oven to produce food products such as bread, cakes, pastries, and pies. These products are often sold from the bakery itself. Additionally, a bakery has a related synonym, bakeshop.
Straw is a type of agricultural environmental material, defined as an agricultural byproduct consisting of the dry stalk of a cereal plant after the nutrient grain or seed has been removed.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:rice_straw rdfs:subClassOf :straw .
text: rice straw is a type of straw.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:farmyard_manure rdfs:subClassOf :animal_manure .
text: farmyard manure is a type of animal manure.

A brewery is a type of industrial building that has a specific definition. A brewery is a building in which alcoholic beverages are produced by brewing, that is, steeping a starch source (commonly cereal grains) in water and fermenting the resulting sweet liquid with yeast. At times, the products are also sold from the brewery.
A cosmetic product is a type of manufactured product that has been formulated to modify the appearance of external human anatomical parts.

The face cream product falls under the category of cosmetic products, characterized by its specific definition. This definition outlines that it is formulated to possess a viscous, fatty, liquid consistency that resembles the fat-rich component of milk. Additionally, it is designed to be applied to human facial skin with the aim of altering its appearance or functioning.
A paper product is a type of manufactured product defined as a product which is composed primarily of paper.
A currency note is a type of paper product which is defined as a paper product used as legal tender in economic or other monetary transactions. It is also exactly synonymous with a bank note.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:rye_grass_silage rdfs:subClassOf :grass_silage .
text: rye grass silage is a type of grass silage.
Aviation fuel is a type of oil and a type of something that at least has some role as fossil fuel. Additionally, aviation fuel is synonymously related to jet fuel.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:poultry_deep_litter rdfs:subClassOf :poultry_litter .
text: poultry deep litter is a type of poultry litter.
A sake brewery is a type of brewery that is defined as a brewery which produces rice wine by fermenting rice that has been polished to remove the bran.

Chalk soil is the same as something that is an intersection of soil and something that at least has increased levels of some chalk. Furthermore, chalk soil is a type of enriched soil and also a type that at least has increased levels of some chalk. Additionally, chalk soil is defined as soil which has increased levels of chalk.
A research station is a type of research facility, defined as a building or collection of co-located buildings constructed for the purpose of undertaking scientific research.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:stable_manure rdfs:subClassOf :animal_manure .
text: stable manure is a type of animal manure.
Scum is a type of environmental material, defined as a layer of impurities that accumulates at the surface of a liquid, especially water or molten metal.
A warehouse is a type of commercial building with the definition that it is a building used for the storage of goods.
A tobacco warehouse is a type of warehouse that is used to store cured leaves of plants from the genus Nicotiana, primarily N. tabacum and N. rustica. This defines a tobacco warehouse.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:anaerobic_digester_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :anaerobic_sludge .
text: anaerobic digester sludge is a type of anaerobic sludge.

A creamery is a type of building part and is also a type of something that is at least part of some dairy. Additionally, a creamery has the definition: "A creamery is a part of a dairy where cream is separated from whole milk."
An air filter is a type of manufactured product and is also a component that forms at least part of some air conditioning units. It is defined as a device that removes some substances from the air.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:potato_silage rdfs:subClassOf :silage .
text: potato silage is a type of silage.

Travertine is a type of limestone that forms as a result of the intersection between a chemical precipitation process and the union of streams and mineral springs, which at least occurs in environments where calcium carbonate is output. Additionally, travertine is defined as limestone that is deposited from the water of mineral springs or streams saturated with calcium carbonate.

A sawmill is a type of industrial building that is specifically designed for processing lumber production. It is defined as a building within which logs are cut into lumber products. This entails that a sawmill encompasses at least some processes involved in the production of lumber.

A karst field, also known exactly as a karst polje, is defined as a large flat plain situated in karst territory, with areas typically ranging from 5 to 400 square kilometres. It is characterized as being the same as an intersection of a plain and an entity that is at least located in some karst. This highlights that a karst field is both a type of plain and a type of entity that is necessarily located in some karst area.
Foamy environmental material, which is a type of environmental material, is defined as an environmental material that possesses the quality of a foam.

Sea foam is a type of foamy environmental material that is found at least in some seas. It is defined as a foamy environmental material that is created by the agitation of seawater, and its stability depends on the content of the seawater.

Paddy field soil is a type of agricultural soil, field soil, and something that is at least part of some paddy field. It is defined as soil which is part of a paddy field and is also known by its related synonym, rice paddy soil.

Alpine soil is a type of soil that intersects with entities that are, at the very least, part of some environmental system and have some alpine quality. It is defined as soil which is part of an alpine environment.
Arable soil is a type of soil defined as soil which is capable of supporting the growth of crops.

Roadside soil is a type of soil that is synonymous with something at the intersection of soil and something that is at least located in some roadside area. Furthermore, roadside soil is defined as a portion of soil which is found in a roadside area.

Allotment garden soil is defined as soil that is part of an allotment garden. It is a type of garden soil and also a type of entity that is at least partially part of some allotment garden. Additionally, allotment garden soil is the same as the intersection of soil and something that is at least partially part of some allotment garden.

An allotment garden is a type of garden, which is defined as a garden made available for individual, non-commercial gardening or growing food plants. It is broadly synonymous with the term "allotment" and is also related to the concept known as a "community garden."

Savanna soil is the same as something that is an intersection of grassland soil and something that is at least located in some savanna. It is a type of grassland soil and also a type of something that is at least located in some savanna. Additionally, savanna soil is defined as a portion of soil which is found in a savanna.
