Compost soil is defined as soil that is derived from compost. It is both a type of soil and a kind that at least derives from some compost. Additionally, compost soil is equivalent to something that intersects something that is soil with something that at least derives from some compost.

Dry soil is identical to something that is an intersection of soil and something that has at least some quality of being dry. It is categorized as a type of soil and also as a type of entity that possesses at least some quality of being dry. Additionally, dry soil is defined as soil which has little to no water content and in which minerals and other soluble chemical entities have either bonded or become adsorbed to solid particles due to insufficient water availability.

Farm soil is the same as something that intersects soil with something that is a union of something belonging to a rangeland biome and something that is at least part of some cropland biome. Additionally, farm soil is a specific type of soil. Furthermore, it is defined as a portion of soil which is part of a cropland or a rangeland biome.

Grassland soil is a type of soil that is characterized by its location in grassland areas and shares the same properties as the intersection of soil and areas at least located in some grassland area. Moreover, grassland soil is defined as a portion of soil found in a grassland.

Jungle soil is a type of soil defined as soil which is part of a densely forested area subject to tropical climate patterns. It is located in areas that are at the intersection of forested and vegetated areas, both of which must exhibit qualities of being tropical and crowded.

Sawah soil is a type of soil that is part of something which is at least partially a union of rice fields and paddy fields. It is defined as soil which is part of a sawah, a wet or irrigated rice field.

Urea-enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of urea, which means it is both a type of enriched soil and a type that has increased levels of urea. This categorizes urea-enriched soil as the intersection between something that enriches soil and something that has, at the very least, higher levels of urea.

Fertilized soil is a type of soil and is characterized as a kind of material that includes, at least in part, substances that are both chemical entities and have a role as fertilizers. Furthermore, fertilized soil is defined as soil that has been amended with fertilizers.

Field soil is described in several ways. Firstly, it is identified as being the same as something that intersects with soil and something that is at least partially part of some agricultural field. Moreover, field soil is characterized as a type of soil and also as a type of something that is at least partially part of some agricultural field. Additionally, field soil is defined as soil which is part of an agricultural field.
Lawn soil is a type of soil that is defined as soil which is formulated to promote the growth of grasses or other plants used to establish managed areas of vegetation.
Bacteria enriched soil is a type of enriched soil, defined as a portion of soil with elevated bacterial abundance.

Alluvial swamp soil is identical to something that is at the intersection of alluvial soil and something that is at least part of a swamp ecosystem. It is a type of alluvial soil and also a type of something that is at least part of some swamp ecosystem. Furthermore, alluvial swamp soil is defined as a portion of alluvial soil which is part of a swamp ecosystem.

Alluvial paddy field soil is defined as alluvial soil that is at least partially part of a paddy field, indicating that it shares characteristics with both alluvial soil and paddy field soil. Specifically, alluvial paddy field soil is a type of alluvial soil as well as a type of paddy field soil. This essentially means that alluvial paddy field soil is the intersection of alluvial soil and paddy field soil, characterized by its unique property of being alluvial soil which is part of a paddy field.

Burned soil is a type of soil and is also a type of something that is at least the output of some combustion process. It is defined as soil which has been transformed through a combustion process. Additionally, burned soil is synonymously related to burnt soil.

Meadow soil is the same as something that intersects with soil and something that is at least a part of some meadow ecosystem. It is a type of soil and also a type of something that is at least a part of some meadow ecosystem. Meadow soil is defined as soil which is part of a meadow.

Chloropicrin enriched soil is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of chloropicrin, which is the same as the intersection of enriched soil and substances that have at least increased levels of chloropicrin. It is a type of enriched soil as well as a type of substance that has increased levels of chloropicrin.

Humus rich acidic ash soil is a type of enriched soil characterized by having increased levels of humus, low pH levels indicating acidity, and increased levels of mineral ash. This soil type embodies qualities that include not only the union of acidic properties and increased acidity but also significant amounts of humus and ash. Essentially, it is defined as soil that prominently features these three attributes.
Pond soil is a type of soil and is something that is at least adjacent to some pond, with its definition being soil which is adjacent to a pond.

Frozen compost soil is defined as compost soil that is frozen. It is a type that intersects with compost soil and with soil that has the quality of being frozen. Essentially, frozen compost soil is a specific kind of both compost soil and frozen soil.
Limed soil is a type of soil defined as soil that has been amended with mineral additives to increase its pH.

Manured soil is defined as soil that, as a part, contains a portion of either fresh or processed animal manure, or a product thereof. It is identical to a category that intersects with soils and those that contain at least a part of either animal manure or an animal manure product. Furthermore, manured soil is classified as a type of soil, as well as a type of substance that must include a part of either animal manure or an animal manure product.
Orchid soil is a type of soil defined as soil which has properties to which plants in the Family Orchidaceae have adapted, including increased levels of aeration and drainage.
Mountain forest soil is a type of forest soil, upland soil, and something that is at least part of some mountain. It is defined as soil which is part of a forest growing on a mountain.
Beech forest soil is a type of forest soil defined as soil which is part of a forest whose communities of arborescent plants are dominated by the genus Fagus.

Muddy soil is a type of soil that is the same as something that intersects soil with something that is at least composed primarily of mud. It is also a type of something that is at least composed primarily of mud. Muddy soil is defined as soil which is composed of a large proportion of mud, thus having properties resembling mud.

Orchard soil is the same as something that is an intersection of something that is soil and something that is at least located in some orchard. Additionally, orchard soil is a type of farm soil and is also a type of something that is at least part of some orchard as well as a type of something that is at least located in some orchard. Moreover, orchard soil has the definition "Soil in which trees from an orchard grow."

Pasture soil is a type of soil that is found in a pasture; it is the same as something that intersects something that is soil and something that is at least located in some pasture. This means that pasture soil is essentially soil that is located within a pasture. It is defined as soil in which vegetation, such as the grass used for the grazing of ungulates, grows.
Peat soil is a type of histosol and it is defined as a histosol formed by the decomposition of vegetation or organic matter. Additionally, it has a broad synonym, turf, and a related synonym, peat.

Salt contaminated soil is recognized as a type of contaminated soil that inherently possesses qualities such as increased osmolarity and elevated levels of sodium chloride. It is defined as soil which has elevated concentrations of sodium chloride, and is also referred to by its synonym, salty soil.
Peaty paddy field soil is a type of enriched and paddy field soil, which is characterized by having increased levels of peat soil. It is defined as paddy field soil that has increased levels of peat.

Steppe soil is the same as something that intersects grassland soil and something that is at least located in a steppe. It is a type of grassland soil and also a type of something that is at least located in some steppe. Moreover, steppe soil is defined as a portion of soil found in a steppe.

Tropical soil is a type of soil defined as soil that is part of a tropical environment. It is considered to be within the intersection of an environmental system and entities that possess the quality of being at least partially tropical.
Vegetable garden soil is a type of garden soil defined as garden soil which is part of a garden used for the cultivation of vegetables.
Greenhouse soil is a type of soil defined as a portion of soil found in a greenhouse.
Heat stressed soil is a type of soil defined as soil which has been heated such that its chemical, physical, or biological properties are destabilized.

Ornithogenic soil is a type of soil that derives from the intersection of fecal material and the output of the excretion process which has birds (Aves) as its causal agent. It is defined as soil that is formed from avian fecal matter.
Leafy wood soil is a type of forest soil, characterized by being part of a woodland dominated by leafy trees.
Spruce forest soil is a type of forest soil defined as soil that is part of a forest whose communities of arborescent plants are dominated by the genus Picea.

Upland soil, a type of soil, shares the same characteristics with something that intersects soil and something that is at least part of some elevated landform. This soil is defined as soil which is part of some elevated land, indicating its classification as a type of soil that is at least part of some elevated landform.
Eucalyptus forest soil is a type of forest soil defined as soil which is part of a forest whose communities of arborescent plants are dominated by the genus Eucalyptus.
Rubber plantation soil is a type of agricultural and farm soil, which is at least a part of some rubber plantation.
Bluegrass field soil is a type of agricultural soil, defined as soil found in a field of Kentucky Bluegrass (Poa pratensis).

Red soil is a type of soil defined by several characteristics: it has low concentrations of nutrients and humus, a low water retention capacity, a textural variation that ranges from sand to clay, a porous and friable structure, and low concentrations of soluble salts.
Sterile water is a type of liquid water and is defined as water that does not contain living organisms.

Underground water is a type of liquid water and is also a type of entity that is located at least in some planetary subsurface zone. It is defined as water which has physicochemical properties determined by processes that occur beneath the planetary crust. Additionally, underground water is related to and can be synonymously referred to as subterranean water.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:muddy_water rdfs:subClassOf :liquid_water .
text: muddy water is a type of liquid water.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:water_scum rdfs:subClassOf :scum .
text: water scum is a type of scum.

Marine mud is defined as mud that is part of a marine ecosystem. It is equivalent to the intersection of something that is mud and something that is at least part of some marine biome. Furthermore, marine mud is a type of mud and also a type of something that is at least part of some marine biome.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:marine_sludge rdfs:subClassOf :sludge .
text: marine sludge is a type of sludge.

Lake bottom mud is the same as something that intersects mud and something that is at least part of some lake bed. It is a type of mud and also a type of something that is at least part of some lake bed. Additionally, lake bottom mud is defined as mud which constitutes the bed of a lake.
Acid dune sand is a type of sand that is part of some dunes and has an acidic quality.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:rocky_sand rdfs:subClassOf :sand .
text: rocky sand is a type of sand.

Desert sand is the same as something that intersects with both sand and something that is at least part of some desert. It is a type of sand and also a type of something that is at least part of some desert. Additionally, desert sand is defined as sand which is part of a desert.

The rhizosphere is a type of environmental zone characterized as a narrow region of soil that is directly influenced by root secretions and associated soil microorganisms. It overlaps with an intersection of ecosystems and is partially determined by both soil and root systems. This indicates that the rhizosphere is a specific zone where the ecosystem interacts closely with soil and root systems due to the influence of root secretions and soil microorganisms.
Bulk soil is a type of soil defined as soil that is not penetrated by the root systems of plants.
Animal habitation refers to a type of construction defined as the dwelling of an animal or group of similar animals. It is closely synonymous with terms such as "den" and "nest."

A nest of ant is a type of animal habitation, defined as a pile of earth, sand, pine needles, or clay, or a composite of these and other materials that build up at the entrances of the subterranean dwellings of ant colonies as they are excavated. This colony is built and maintained by legions of worker ants, who carry tiny bits of dirt and pebbles in their mandibles and deposit them near the exit of the colony. They normally deposit the dirt or vegetation at the top of the hill to prevent it from sliding back into the colony. However, in some species, they actively sculpt the materials into specific shapes and may create nest chambers within the mound. The nest of an ant also has the exact synonym "ant's nest" and is relatedly known as an "ant hill."

A nest of a bird is a type of animal habitation which is defined as the spot in which a bird lays and incubates its eggs and raises its young. It is exactly synonymous with "bird nest" and "bird's nest." Additionally, "nest of bird" has a narrow synonym, "eyrie."

Ice rise is a type of elevated landform, surface landform, and something that is at least part of some ice shelf. It is defined as an elevation that is part of an ice shelf, typically dome-shaped, and formed by the ice shelf overriding an obstruction in the seabed. An ice rise may be adjacent only to an ice shelf, or to an ice shelf and a sea. For some features, properly termed ice rises, the term island has become established through usage.

An ice piedmont is a type of glacier defined as a glacier that covers a coastal strip of low-lying land backed by mountains. It slopes gently seaward over a distance up to 30km or more to either terminate in ice cliffs or to merge with an ice shelf.

A strand crack is a type of geological fracture defined as a fissure at the junction between an inland ice sheet, ice piedmont or ice rise, and an ice shelf, with the latter being subject to the rise and fall of the tide.

Soil bulk density is a characteristic that intersects with volumetric density and is at least characteristic of some soil. It is both a type of mass density and a type of volumetric density of soil. Soil bulk density is defined as a volumetric density quality which inheres in soil by virtue of some influence exerted by the soil's mass on a given volume. Additionally, soil bulk density has an exact synonym: soil compaction.

A fomite is a type of object defined as any inanimate object or substance capable of carrying infectious organisms, such as germs or parasites, thereby transferring them from one individual to another. It is important to remember that fomites can include various items, such as cloths or mop heads, which could aid in the spreading of pathogenic organisms when cleaning.

A midden is a type of anthropogenic geographic feature, defined as a dump for domestic waste. It is a term used to describe any kind of feature containing waste products relating to day-to-day human life.

Environmental material is identified as a type of fiat object part and is also recognized as a type of entity that is at least primarily composed of some macromolecule. It is defined as a portion of environmental material, which constitutes a fiat object part that forms the medium or a part of the medium of an environmental system. Additionally, environmental material is exactly synonymous with the term "portion of environmental material."

The surface layer, which is a type of interface layer, is defined as a layer of some material entity that is adjacent to one or more of its external boundaries and directly interacts with its immediate surroundings.

Aerosol is identified as a type of environmental material that encompasses at least a portion of gaseous environmental materials. Additionally, it includes parts that are an intersection of particulate environmental materials and entities that are at least surrounded by some gaseous environmental materials. Aerosol is also characterized by having an amorphous quality. Furthermore, it is defined as airborne solid particles, also referred to as dust or particulate matter (PM), or liquid droplets.

Emulsion is a type of environmental material defined as a mixture of two immiscible (unblendable) substances, where one substance (the dispersed phase) is dispersed in the other (the continuous phase).
A medical instrument is a type of manufactured product that is defined as a product designed for use in one or more medical procedures.

A vivarium serves as a biomaterial containment unit and is characterized by having at least some environment control function. It is defined as an enclosure for keeping and raising organisms for observation or research. Typically, a vivarium simulates a portion of the ecosystem for a particular species on a smaller scale, incorporating controls for environmental conditions.
Dolomite is a type of sedimentary rock and a mineral, both defined as a sedimentary carbonate rock composed of calcium magnesium carbonate CaMg(CO3)2, found in crystals.

A botanical garden, which is a type of garden, is defined as a place where a wide variety of plants are primarily categorized and documented for scientific purposes. It also has the exact synonym "botanic garden."

A zoological garden, which is a type of garden, is defined as a facility in which animals are confined within enclosures and displayed to the public, and in which they may also be bred. It has the exact synonyms "zoo" and "zoological park."

An ocean time series station is a type of research facility, defined as a research facility consisting of instruments that measure the properties of the oceans over time, usually of at least approximately fixed location.

An aquifer is a type of solid layer that at least has parts of both the vadose zone and the phreatic zone. Furthermore, it is composed primarily of materials that are a union of soil, clay, mud, silt, gravel, and a specific type of rock that is characterized by having a porous quality. An aquifer is defined as an underground layer of water-bearing permeable rock or unconsolidated materials, such as gravel, sand, silt, or clay, from which groundwater can be usefully extracted using a water well.
A karst cave is a type of cave and also a type of something that is at least part of some karst. Moreover, it is defined as a cave which is part of a karst formation.

Anthropogenic environmental material is defined as material in or on which organisms may live and is considered the same as something that intersects environmental material with something that is at least an output of something that is a union of anthropisation and a manufacturing process. Moreover, it is a type of environmental material and also a type of something that is at least an output of something that unites anthropisation and a manufacturing process.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:agricultural_environmental_material rdfs:subClassOf :anthropogenic_environmental_material .
text: agricultural environmental material is a type of anthropogenic environmental material.

A dry stream valley is a type of dry valley and also falls under the category of formations that occur due to the intersection of erosion and the involvement of a stream. It is defined as a dry valley which was formed as a result of erosion due to stream formation and flow.

A dry river valley is a specific type of dry stream valley, characterized by its formation due to the intersection of erosion and river activity. It is defined as a dry stream valley which emerged as a result of erosion caused by the formation and flow of a river.

Humus is a type of solid environmental material and a form of soil organic matter, which at least partly derives from plant matter fall. It is defined as organic matter in soil that has reached a point of stability, where it will no longer break down further and, if conditions remain constant, could essentially remain as it is for centuries or even millennia.

Mud is a type of environmental material that is characterized by being a liquid or semi-liquid mixture of water and some combination of soil, silt, and clay particles. It is a material that, at the very least, includes parts of soil and liquid water.
A water well is a type of well and also a kind of entity that at least partially overlaps some aquifer. It is defined as a well which provides access to groundwater held in an aquifer.
An oil well is a type of well with a definition that specifies it as a well drilled for the purpose of extracting petroleum oil from subterranean reservoirs and bringing it to the surface.

The concentration basin Mediterranean Sea biome is a type of Mediterranean Sea biome that is defined by its higher salinity compared to adjacent oceans, a result of evaporation. This biome features a water exchange mechanism involving the inflow of fresher oceanic water in the upper layer and the outflow of the saltier Mediterranean water in the lower layer of the connecting channel.

Upwelling, also precisely known as marine upwelling, is a type of ocean current characterized by an oceanographic feature that entails the wind-driven motion of dense, cooler, and usually nutrient-rich water towards the ocean surface, replacing the warmer, usually nutrient-deplete surface water. This phenomenon occurs as a net flow of marine water to the surface of the water column from deeper regions, often resulting from surface water displacement off continental coasts by wind action. Localized upwellings may also occur along divergent fronts around eddies and along some of the major oceanographic features. Given that deeper waters often have higher nutrient content, blooms of primary producers, such as planktonic algae, are generally observed around upwelling zones.

Coastal upwelling is the same as the intersection of upwelling and something that is at least adjacent to some sea coast. It is both a type of upwelling and a type of phenomenon that is at least adjacent to some sea coast. Furthermore, coastal upwelling is defined as an upwelling that is near a coast.

An organic object formed through microbial activity is a type of organic object, which is defined as an organic object that is formed as a result of the biological processes mediated by microbial assemblages. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym "microbial feature."

A microbial mat is a type of mass of biological material, defined as a multi-layered sheet of micro-organisms, primarily bacteria and archaea. These mats grow at interfaces between different types of material, predominantly on submerged or moist surfaces, though some can survive in deserts.

Silt is a type of particulate environmental material, which is primarily composed of silt particles and has a definition as such. It is a type of substance that, at the very least, contains some particles of silt, exhibits some texture, and possesses some porous quality. Additionally, silt is distinctly different from sand, indicating that the two are separate entities with no overlap.

Sand is a type of particulate environmental material and is defined as a particulate environmental material composed primarily of particles of sand with only minor proportions of other substances. It is a type of something that at least has part some particle of sand and derives from something that is a union of rock, organism, and shell. Additionally, sand is characterized by having a texture, being porous, and being granular.

Gravel is an environmental material characterized by several key features. It is a type of material that includes, at a minimum, parts that are pieces of gravel. Additionally, gravel possesses qualities such as being porous and granular. Furthermore, gravel is defined as an environmental material primarily composed of pieces of gravel.

A cave floor is a type of solid surface layer that also qualifies as a surface of an astronomical body. It is part of a cave, characterized by at least some quality of horizontality. The cave floor's definition includes being a solid surface layer that forms part of the boundary between the cavity of a cave and its solid container, and it is the closest solid boundary to the gravitational center of the astronomical body of which the cave is a part.

The estuarine biome is a type of marine biome, characterized by its occurrence at the wide lower courses of rivers where they flow into the sea. Estuaries are defined by experiencing tidal flows and having water that is a changing mixture of fresh and salt.

The marine salt marsh biome is a type of marine biome defined as comprising marshes that are transitional intertidals between land and salty or brackish marine water, such as sloughs, bays, and estuaries. It is characterized by the dominance of halophytic (salt tolerant) herbaceous plants. The biome benefits from daily tidal surges that bring in nutrients, which tend to settle in the roots of the plants within the salt marsh. Additionally, the natural chemical activity of salty or brackish water and the tendency of algae to bloom in the shallow, unshaded water contribute to a high level of biodiversity within this biome.

The marine pelagic biome is a type of marine biome and also a type of entity that at least has part of some marine water body. It is defined as the marine pelagic biome (pelagic meaning open sea), which encompasses the marine water column from the surface to the greatest depths.

The marine benthic biome, which is a type of marine biome, is defined as encompassing the seafloor and includes areas such as shores, littoral or intertidal areas, marine coral reefs, and the deep seabed, with "benthic" meaning 'bottom'.

The marine neritic benthic zone biome is a specific type of marine benthic biome. It is defined as the area of the sea floor that extends from the high tide mark to the break of the continental shelf, generally reaching up to 200 meters below the average sea level.

The marine bathyal zone biome, which is a type of marine benthic biome, is defined as comprising regions of the marine benthic biome between approximately 200 m and 3000 m depth. This zone generally coincides with the continental slope.

The marine abyssal zone biome, a type of marine benthic biome, is defined as comprising regions between approximately 2500 m and 6000 m depth. This zone generally coincides with the continental rise and the abyssal plain.
The marine hadal zone biome is a type of marine benthic biome. It is defined as the sea floor deeper than 6000 meters, such as those found in oceanic trenches.

The marine reef biome is a type of marine benthic biome and also a type of something that is at least determined by some marine reef. It is defined as a biome expressed by strips or ridges of rocks, sand, or coral that rises to or near the surface of a body of marine water.

The marine hydrothermal vent biome is a specific type of marine benthic biome. It is defined by areas within the marine benthic biome where heat, generated by tectonic activity at either divergent plate boundaries or convergent ocean plates with back-arc spreading, is released to the surface. This process results in high-temperature water jets that are rich in dissolved metals and minerals.
The neritic pelagic zone biome, which is a type of marine pelagic biome, comprises the marine water column above a continental shelf. It is distinct and disjoint from the oceanic pelagic zone biome.
The oceanic pelagic zone biome, which is a type of marine pelagic biome, is defined as the area comprising the marine water column offshore, beyond a continental shelf.

The oceanic sea surface microlayer biome, which is a type of oceanic pelagic zone biome, is defined as the oceanic sea surface microlayer (SML) biome encompassing the top 1000 micrometers of the marine surface waters occurring offshore, away from a continental shelf. It serves as the boundary layer where all exchanges between the atmosphere and the ocean occur. The chemical, physical, and biological properties of the SML differ significantly from the sub-surface water located just a few centimeters beneath.

The oceanic epipelagic zone biome is a specific type of oceanic pelagic zone biome, characterized by its location in regions of the marine water column that are offshore, beyond the continental shelf, and extending from the ocean's surface to a depth of approximately 200-250 meters. This biome is notable for its vertically asymmetrical light field, which allows the direction and elevation of the sun to be detected within it. Additionally, the oceanic epipelagic zone biome includes the euphotic zone and, depending on the occurrence, the seasonal thermocline.

The oceanic mesopelagic zone biome is a specific type of oceanic pelagic zone biome. It is defined as comprising regions of the marine water column that are located offshore, beyond a continental shelf, extending through the water column from approximately 200 to 1000 meters in depth. This depth range represents the maximal depth of light penetration in all but the clearest oligotrophic ocean regions. Although there are not very significant changes in the dominant forms of pelagic organisms when compared to the epipelagic zone, there are noticeable changes in species composition, and the proportion of smaller-sized individuals decreases.

The oceanic bathypelagic zone biome is a specific type of oceanic pelagic zone biome. It is defined as the marine water column that lies below approximately 1000 meters water depth, where detectable daylight can no longer penetrate except in the clearest oligotrophic waters, and extends down to about 2500 to 2700 meters water depth. Notably, in the temperate Atlantic, the start of the bathypelagic zone biome is approximately marked by the deep oxygen minimum and the base of the permanent thermocline.

The oceanic abyssopelagic zone biome is a specific type of oceanic pelagic zone biome. It is defined as the marine water column that lies below the bathypelagic zone biome at approximately 2500-2700 meters and extends either to the hadal pelagic zone biome at approximately 6000 meters or to the benthopelagic zone biome within about 100 meters of the seafloor. The depth of 2700 meters is considered significant for physiological reasons, as the change in hydrostatic pressure across this depth may prevent organism migration.
The oceanic hadal pelagic zone biome is a type of oceanic pelagic zone biome. It is defined as comprising the water column in oceanic trenches that occur at depths between 6,000m and 10,000m.

The oceanic benthopelagic zone biome is a type of oceanic pelagic zone biome, defined as comprising regions of the marine water column which usually coincide with the benthic boundary layer (BBL). This layer is characterized by isothermal and isohaline water contiguous to the sea floor. In this zone, a general reversal in the declining gradient of pelagic biomass may be observed, which could be explained by viable nutrition on the sea floor being resuspended by bottom currents. Typically, the benthopelagic zone extends 100 m above the seafloor, but it may reach up to 1000 m during benthic storms.

The neritic sea surface microlayer biome, which is a type of neritic pelagic zone biome, is defined as comprising the top 1000 micrometers of marine surface waters occurring above a continental shelf. This biome serves as the boundary layer where all exchanges occur between the atmosphere and the ocean, and it is noted that the chemical, physical, and biological properties of the sea surface microlayer (SML) differ greatly from the sub-surface water just a few centimeters beneath.

The neritic epipelagic zone biome is a specific type of neritic pelagic zone biome. This biome is defined as the marine water column situated above a continental shelf, stretching from the ocean surface down to approximately 200-250m in depth. Characteristically, within this zone, there exists a vertically asymmetrical light field, allowing for the direction and elevation of the sun to be perceived. Furthermore, the epipelagic zone includes the euphotic zone and may also encompass the seasonal thermocline where it occurs.

The neritic mesopelagic zone biome is a subtype of the neritic pelagic zone biome. It is defined as the marine column located above a continental shelf, stretching from roughly 200 to 1000 meters in depth, which represents the maximum depth that light can penetrate in all but the clearest oligotrophic ocean regions. Compared to the epipelagic zone, the dominant forms of pelagic organisms remain relatively consistent in the neritic mesopelagic zone biome. However, there are significant changes in species composition, and the proportion of smaller-sized individuals decreases.

The epeiric sea biome, which is a type of marine biome, is defined as comprising shallow seas that extend over part of a continent. These seas, also known as epicontinental seas, are usually associated with marine transgressions of the geologic past, which have been caused by global eustatic sea level changes, local tectonic deformation, or both, and are occasionally semi-cyclic. Furthermore, the epeiric sea biome has an exact synonym: epicontinental sea biome.

The marginal sea biome is identified as a type of marine biome and is defined by the characteristics that make it distinct. Specifically, the marginal sea biome includes parts of an ocean that are partially enclosed by land formations such as islands, archipelagos, or peninsulas. A key feature that sets marginal seas apart from Mediterranean seas is the presence of ocean currents that are driven by ocean winds. Moreover, it is noted that many marginal seas are surrounded by island arcs, which are the result of the subduction of one oceanic plate beneath another.

The Mediterranean Sea biome is both a type of marine biome and a type of Mediterranean biome. It is defined as comprising mostly enclosed seas that have limited exchange of deep water with outer oceans, with water circulation being dominated by salinity and temperature differences rather than winds.

The ocean biome is identical to an entity that is at the intersection of a biome and something that is at least determined by an ocean. It is a type of marine biome and is also categorized as a type that is determined by an ocean. Additionally, the ocean biome is defined as a marine biome which is determined by an ocean.

The marine coral reef biome is a specific type of marine reef biome, defined by comprising constructional wave-resistant entities primarily built by corals, often cemented together. The growth of these structures is aided by zooxanthellae, algae that are symbiotic with the reef-building corals.

The marine subtidal rocky reef biome is a type of marine reef biome defined as regions within the marine reef biome primarily composed of rock. These regions harbor abundant communities of algae and invertebrates, characterized by their patchy nature, with alternating areas dominated by rich invertebrate assemblages and turf-forming calcareous red algae.

The marine black smoker biome is a subtype of the marine hydrothermal vent biome. It is defined by areas within the marine hydrothermal vent biome that are distinguished by a black vent plume. This black plume results from dissolved metals and minerals combining with sulphide, signaling the presence of polymetallic sulphide mineral deposits below the surface.

The marine white smoker biome is a specific type of marine hydrothermal vent biome. It is defined by regions within the marine hydrothermal vent biome that are characterized by lightly colored plumes, usually containing barium, calcium, and silicon. Notably, these vents are distinguished by their lower temperature plumes compared to those found in black smoker environments.

The marine ultramafic hydrothermal vent biome is a specific category within the broader marine hydrothermal vent biome. It is characterized by being situated on ultramafic rocks, which are igneous and meta-igneous rocks notable for their very low silica content of less than 45%, generally more than 18% MgO, high FeO, low potassium, and predominantly composed of more than 90% mafic minerals. These minerals are dark-colored with high magnesium and iron content, similar to the composition of the Earth's mantle.

The marine basaltic hydrothermal vent biome is a specific type of marine hydrothermal vent biome. This biome is characterized by regions that are situated on basaltic rocks. Basalt, the rock foundation of these biomes, typically features a composition that includes 45 to 55 weight percent (wt%) of SiO2, 2 to 6 wt% of total alkalis, 0.5 to 2.0 wt% of TiO2, 5 to 14 wt% of FeO, and at least 14 wt% of Al2O3. Additionally, the content of CaO in basalt is usually around 10 wt%, while the content of MgO is commonly found in the range of 5 to 12 wt%.

Marine algal bloom is identical to the intersection of an algal bloom and entities located in a marine biome, and it is a specific type of algal bloom as well as a type of entity found in marine biomes. The definition of a marine algal bloom is a rapid increase or accumulation in the population of algae within a marine system, usually involving only one or a small number of phytoplankton species. Although there is no official threshold, a bloom may be considered when algae concentrations reach hundreds to thousands of cells per milliliter, varying with severity. Additionally, marine algal bloom is narrowly referred to as red tide.

A kelp forest is a type of undersea feature, defined as underwater areas with a high density of kelp. They are recognized as one of the most productive and dynamic ecosystems on Earth. Smaller areas of anchored kelp within these forests are referred to as kelp beds, which is a related synonym.

A sea grass bed is a type of marine bed and it is also a type of entity that is part of some entity which is the union of the ocean floor and the sea floor. It is defined as a bed of a marine, saline water body which is covered by one or more species of seagrass, typically belonging to the families Posidoniaceae, Zosteraceae, Hydrocharitaceae, or Cymodoceaceae. Additionally, sea grass bed has exact synonyms including seagrass bed and seagrass meadow.

Particulate environmental material is a type of environmental material and is also a type of substance that possesses, at least in part, particles and has a granular quality. It is defined as an environmental material which is composed primarily of particles. Furthermore, particulate environmental material is broadly synonymous with particulate matter.

The marine wind mixed layer is a type of marine layer and also a part of the marine photic zone. It is defined as the upper part of the marine water column with generally uniform properties resulting from wind-driven mixing. This layer is also known exactly as the epipelagic mixed layer.

A marine benthic storm is a type of marine current defined as strong benthic (near bottom) currents that transport sediment, created by the input of energy (largely kinetic) to the seabed. In regions with high mesoscale eddy activity, benthic storms are frequent and can create isohaline and isothermal conditions extending as much as 1000m above the seafloor.
Planktonic material, which is a type of organic material, is defined as a portion of environmental material primarily composed of plankton.

Marine downwelling is a type of marine current, characterized as a net current of marine surface water moving towards deeper regions of the water column. This phenomenon is typically induced by differences in the density of seawater, which are influenced by variations in temperature and salinity.

The marine oxygen minimum zone is a type of marine water mass, hydroform, and a part of a marine water body. It is characterized by having a quality that intersects with decreased concentration and characteristics of sea water, particularly towards something that intersects with dioxygen and has the quality of being dissolved. Additionally, the marine oxygen minimum zone is defined as a marine water mass characterized by persistently much lower than normal dissolved oxygen concentrations.

A marine anoxic zone is a type of marine environmental zone, also recognized as a component within at least a part of some marine water bodies. It is defined as areas of marine water that are depleted of dissolved oxygen, a condition typically found in regions with restricted water exchange. This lack of oxygen is often due to a physical barrier, such as a sill, combined with pronounced density stratification, leading to anoxic conditions when the oxidation of organic matter by bacteria exceeds the supply of dissolved oxygen. Furthermore, the marine anoxic zone is synonymously related to a "dead zone."

A marine current is a type of water current and is also a type of something that is at least composed primarily of sea water. It is defined as a water current which is maintained by a continuous, directed movement of marine water, generated by forces caused by breaking waves, wind, the Coriolis force, temperature and salinity differences, and tides caused by the gravitational pull of astronomical bodies. The direction and strength of a marine current are influenced by depth contours, shoreline configurations, and interactions with other currents.

A marine streamer is a type of marine current characterized by tongues of cold water that extend more than 100 kilometers offshore from upwelling regions. These waters are typically more nutrient-rich than marine surface waters, which may lead to enhanced primary productivity.

Mesoscale marine eddy, a type of marine current, is defined by its characteristic currents that flow in a roughly circular motion around the eddy's center. These currents may rotate either cyclonically or anticyclonically. Furthermore, ocean eddies typically consist of water masses distinct from those outside the eddy. In terms of size, marine mesoscale eddies range between approximately 10 and 500 km in diameter and can persist for days to months. Their formation is attributed to the development of instability in an ocean current, which leads to meandering. Eventually, this instability causes an eddy to be pinched off from the meandering current.
Terrigenous sediment is a type of sediment defined as sediment comprised of weathered continental rocks, wind-blown dust, volcanic ash, or other terrestrial material.

An oceanic front is a type of fluid cline and also falls under the category of phenomena that are, at least partially, an intersection of ocean and sea. It is defined as a narrow zone of enhanced horizontal gradients of water properties such as temperature, salinity, nutrients, among others, which separates broader areas that possess different water masses or different vertical structures, known as stratification.

A marine Taylor column is the same as something that intersects a Taylor column and something that is at least located in some marine water body. It is a type of Taylor column and also a type of entity that is located in a marine water body. The definition of a marine Taylor column is as follows: A marine Taylor column is formed in a marine body of water when currents flowing over shoaling topography, such as seamounts, are accelerated and destabilized, leading to the formation of Taylor columns. This process generates eddies and internal waves downstream of the topological feature, which may extend up to 1000 m or so above them. This phenomenon can result in a localized increase in primary production where the Taylor column reaches surface waters.

A marine oligotrophic desert is a type of marine water mass characterized by being primarily composed of oligotrophic water, which has low concentrations of nutrients. This classification places it within a category that intersects with both oceans and seas. In essence, it is defined as a marine water mass characterized by its low nutrient content.

An oceanic gyre is a type of marine current with a specific definition in oceanography. It refers to any large system of rotating ocean currents, especially those associated with significant wind movements. The formation of gyres is influenced by the Coriolis Effect, planetary vorticity, and both horizontal and vertical friction, which together determine the circulation patterns from the wind curl (torque).

Marine thermocline is a type of thermocline and also a type of marine cline. It is the same as the intersection of a thermocline and at least part of some marine water body. Additionally, marine thermocline is defined as a thermocline which is part of a marine water body.

The marine chemocline is identical to the intersection of a chemocline and at least part of some marine water body. It is a type of chemocline as well as a type of marine cline. The definition of a marine chemocline is as follows: A marine chemocline is a marine cline caused by a strong, vertical chemistry gradient within a body of marine water. Chemoclines most commonly occur where local conditions favor the formation of anoxic bottom water.

A marine pycnocline is a specific type of pycnocline, aquatic layer, and marine cline, characterized by being at least partly composed of sea water. It is defined as a pycnocline that is part of a marine water body and primarily made up of sea water. Furthermore, it is identical to an intersection involving a pycnocline and an entity that is at least partially part of some marine water body.
A marine nutricline is a type of nutricline and a type of marine cline within a water body. It is defined as a nutricline which is part of a marine water body.

A marine lysocline is a specific type of lysocline. It is defined as the depth in the ocean below which the rate of dissolution of calcite increases dramatically. This phenomenon occurs because, as the depth of the water column and consequently the pressure increases, the calcite saturation of seawater decreases, leading to the dissolution of calcite.

The pelagic isothermal surface is a type of aquatic layer, isothermal surface, and something that is at least part of some water body. It is defined as a roughly planar, pelagic region characterized by equal water temperature.

The pelagic isohaline surface is a type of aquatic layer, isohaline surface, and something that is at least part of some water body. It is defined as a roughly planar, pelagic region characterized by equal salinity.
Biogenous sediment is a type of sediment defined as being derived from living organisms, typically planktonic organisms possessing shells, frustules, or coccoliths.

The pelagic isopycnal surface is a type of aquatic layer, isopycnal surface, and something that constitutes at least part of some water body. It is defined as a roughly planar, pelagic region characterized by equal water density.

Deep ocean current, a type of marine current, is defined as a marine current that generally occurs below the permanent thermocline or below 400 m depth and is driven by density and temperature gradients.

Marine surface current is a type of marine current defined as a marine current that is bordered by the surface of the water column and the permanent thermocline, where it occurs. These surface currents are predominantly wind-driven and are generally confined to the top 400 meters of the water column. The driving force behind ocean currents is the circulation of wind above surface waters. This occurs due to frictional stress at the interface between the ocean and the wind, causing the water to move in the direction of the wind. Large ocean currents emerge as a response of the atmosphere and ocean to the energy flow from the tropics to polar regions. While some currents may be transient features affecting only a small area, others are essentially permanent and extend over large horizontal distances.
An along front current is a type of marine surface current, which is defined as a marine surface current that flows along an oceanic front.

Western boundary current is a type of warm surface current, defined as a warm water, narrow marine surface current that flows from the equator to high latitudes at speeds between 40 and 120 kilometers per day. These currents are the deepest ocean surface flows, usually extending 1000 meters below the ocean surface.

An eastern boundary current is a type of cold surface current that is defined as a cold water, broad marine surface current flowing from high latitudes to the equator at speeds between 3 and 7 kilometers per day.

A permanent marine thermocline is a specific type of marine thermocline that is adjacent to both the marine cold water sphere and the marine warm water sphere. It is defined as a marine thermocline that separates the marine cold-water sphere from the marine warm-water sphere and does not dissipate seasonally.

The seasonal marine thermocline is a specific type of marine thermocline that is characterized by its presence below the marine wind mixed layer. Additionally, it is considered to be adjacent or at least in close proximity to some marine wind mixed layer. Its definition highlights that it is a marine thermocline which becomes apparent beneath the marine wind mixed layer.

The marine cold water sphere is a type of marine water mass that is at least partially encompassed by the union of oceans and seas and is at least adjacent to the marine thermocline. The definition of the marine cold water sphere describes it as a water mass that extends from the polar seas across low latitudes at depths of approximately 800 to 1000 meters. It is separated from the marine warm-water sphere by the permanent marine thermocline.

The marine warm water sphere is a type of marine water mass that is adjacent to the marine thermocline. It is defined as a water mass extending to depths of approximately 800 to 1000 meters in low and middle latitudes, separated from the marine cold-water sphere by the permanent marine thermocline.

Hydrogenous sediment is a type of sediment with a specific definition: it is derived from solutes that precipitate out of seawater through a variety of chemical reactions. These sediments are typically less abundant than other sediment types.
Cosmogenous sediment is a type of sediment that is defined as being derived from extraterrestrial dust and debris, including meteorites and similar entities.

A polymetallic nodule, also known as a manganese nodule, is a type of hydrogenous sediment that is primarily composed of manganese atoms. Polymetallic nodules are rock concretions found on the sea bottom, characterized by concentric layers of iron and manganese hydroxides around a core. These nodules can vary in size, ranging from tiny particles only visible under a microscope to large pellets over 20 centimeters (8 inches) across, although most nodules are between 5 and 10 cm in diameter.

Suspended sediment is a type of sediment defined as suspended load. It refers to particles that settle slowly enough to be carried in flowing water, such as a stream or coastal area, either without touching the bed or while only intermittently touching it. These particles are generally of the fine sand, silt, and clay size, although larger particles may also be carried depending on the intensity of the flow.
Boulder sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by an average particle diameter greater than 256 mm. It is primarily composed of boulders.
Cobble sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by an average particle diameter between 64 and 256 mm.
Pebble sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by an average particle diameter between 4 and 32 mm.
Granular sediment is a type of sediment characterized by an average particle diameter between 2 and 4 mm.
Sandy sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by an average particle diameter between 62.5 micrometers and 2 mm.
Silty sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by an average particle diameter between 3.9 and 62.5 micrometers.
Clay sediment is a type of sediment that is primarily composed of clay. It is defined as sediment characterized by an average particle diameter between 1 and 3.9 micrometers.
Colloidal sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by an average particle diameter below 1 micrometer.

A marine hydrothermal vent is both a type of hydrothermal vent and a type that is located within a marine biome. Additionally, it is defined as a marine benthic feature where heat generated due to tectonic activity, either at divergent plate boundaries or convergent ocean plates where back-arc spreading occurs, is released or 'vented' to the surface, leading to high-temperature water jets that are rich in dissolved metals and minerals. This definition essentially encapsulates the intersection of being a hydrothermal vent and being located in a marine biome.

The marine sponge reef biome, a type of marine reef biome, is characterized by marine reefs primarily constructed by marine sponges. These primary frame-building sponges belong to the order Hexactinosa and are exclusively located in glacier-scoured troughs along the low-angle continental shelf. The biome's seafloor is stable, comprising rock, coarse gravel, and large boulders.

The marine supra littoral zone is a type of environmental zone found within the marine ecosystem. It is a specific part of the marine littoral zone and is adjacent to the marine eulittoral zone. The marine supra littoral zone is defined as the area above the spring high tide line that is regularly splashed, but not submerged by ocean water. Seawater penetrates these elevated areas only during storms with high tides. It is broadly synonymous with the supralittoral zone and has the exact synonym of marine supralittoral zone. Additionally, it is relatedly referred to as the splash zone, spray zone, and the supratidal zone.

The marine littoral zone is categorized as a type of littoral zone and is also recognized as a type of entity that encompasses, at a minimum, a portion of the intertidal zone. It is defined as a littoral zone which stretches, approximately, from the spray region above the high tide mark to the edge of the continental shelf.

The marine sublittoral zone, also known as the sublittoral zone or its exact synonym marine sublittoral zone, is a specific type of marine environmental zone. It forms part of the marine littoral zone and is at least partially included or adjacent to the marine eulittoral zone. The definition of the marine sublittoral zone encompasses the portion of the marine littoral zone that is permanently submerged under seawater. From the perspective of physical oceanography, it includes coastal areas characterized by significant tidal flows and energy dissipation, such as non-linear flows, internal waves, river outflows, and oceanic fronts, typically extending to the edge of the continental shelf at depths around 200 meters. In marine biology, the sublittoral zone refers to the seabed areas within the photic zone, where sunlight is sufficient for photosynthesis, indicating that the water is never so deep as to be outside the photic zone.

The marine cold seep biome is a type of marine benthic biome and is also characterized as a type of entity that includes, at least in part, some cold seep. Furthermore, it is defined as a marine benthic biome that is determined by a cold seep.

The dilution basin Mediterranean Sea biome is a type of Mediterranean Sea biome defined by its lower salinity compared to the surrounding ocean, attributed to freshwater gains from sources like rainfall and rivers. This biome is characterized by a water exchange process involving the outflow of fresher Mediterranean water in the upper layer and the inflow of saltier oceanic water in the lower layer of the channel. However, the renewal of deep water in this biome may not be sufficient to supply oxygen to the bottom.

A marine hydrothermal vent chimney is a type of submerged landform, which is part of a marine hydrothermal vent, exhibits a columnar quality, and is located in a marine benthic biome. It is defined as a column of solid material that has been progressively deposited around a hydrothermal vent.

A marine hydrothermal plume is a type of hydroform and is at least part of some marine hydrothermal vent. It is defined as a marine hydrothermal vent plume, which is part of a marine hydrothermal vent, and is characterized as a high-temperature water jet laden with dissolved metals and minerals. This plume is driven by heat generated due to tectonic activity below the vent.
Mesophilic sediment is a type of sediment defined as sediment characterized by a temperature of 15-45 degrees Celsius and high-to-low oxygenation, often impacted by hydrothermal fluid flows.
Thermophilic sediment is a type of sediment characterized by a temperature of 45-75 degrees Celsius and low to no oxygen content, often impacted by hydrothermal fluid flows.
Hyperthermophilic sediment is a type of sediment that is characterized by a temperature of 80-125 degrees Celsius and no oxygen content. It is often impacted by hydrothermal fluid flows.
